books
i am constantly reading something. what else are you going to do in those daily gaps in your life? (don't say "internet.") anyway, reading is magical, like tapping into the brain of a person you'll probably never meet. here's what i've read recently:
really dense, boring, scientifically accurate scifi
had a(n) historical non fiction kick for a while
read this teen romance novel that made me cry
finally read some chuck klosterman to find out what everybody back in college was talking about
now i'm reading some mark twain
i'd really like to read some contemporary fiction next, something good that affects me. like maybe you should message me if you have suggestions because reading suggestions are the best.

movies
firstly, bad movies. i cannot get enough of bad movies. i might have a fetish for digital rips of color-bled vhs tapes. 80s kung fu, 70s scifi, godzilla, gamera, the blob, anything with a budget around 1000 dollars that takes place in outer space, you get the idea. message me if you want to have an everything is terrible or mystery science theatre 3000 night. even if you suck it would probably make my week.
i do love a good, slow paced art movie though. early 60s mystery and late 60s heist films are my new kick. movies that build up my anticipation, or make me hold my breath, or scare me with what i'm not allowed to see are the best.
ever notice that romantic comedies and comedy commodes are either great or awful? well anyway, thankfully i enjoy both great and awful movies, but don't ever expect me to shut up about what i thought about em. including during the movie, constantly, if it's bad.
oh and documentaries! i watch documentaries constantly. you always learn, and sometimes they're really haunting, you know?

d)
(in order of decreasing volume) water (often tinctured with naturally caffeinated substances), grains, vegetables, the flesh of deceased animals, alcohol, refined sugars, minerals. i try to follow michael pollan's rule (which i take the liberty of paraphrasing here): if someone's grandparents (not necessarily yours or mine) wouldn't recognize it as food, don't eat it. what we often think of as "ethnic" cuisines are really just (approximations of) traditional diets from around the world. this makes them both tasty and fairly healthy.

beyond that, there's a mercifully short list of ingredients that *are* real foods that i still haven't learned to like (e.g., raw carrots or bananas).

essay6:
politics. seriously, shrub's fucked us good. the democrats gambled and won: the margin of victory was large enough to deter the election fraud we saw in the last two presidential elections. the dems are no panacea: nader (and others) are right when the point out that they are just as beholden to their corporate backers as the gop, but at least the next supreme court appointment won't result in roe v. wade being overturned.

language. i'm slowly making my way through all of steven pinker's books.

ethics. pinker seems to be branching into this field as well, though i've read more on this subject by the likes of richard dawkins and douglas adams.

alternative relationship structures. i'm always stunned how widely polyamory (by whatever name) is practiced compared to how few representations there are of it in literature, music, film, theater, etc. there's plenty of coverage of people cheating, but rarely of anybody doing anything as outlandish as *agreeing* to a non-exclusive relationship.

what i want from romantic/sexual relationships. i'm not fickle, per se, but i tend to want very different things from different people.

here are some possibilities:
1.) love. i'm open to feeling and expressing love if we're highly compatible intellectually, emotionally and sexually. (i've already got a primary partner, so if i were to embark in this direction with someone, the relationship would never include cohabitation.)
2.) friendship and sex. much like the above, but neither of us feels inspired to use the l-word.
3.) fuck-buddies. we respect each other; we like each other well enough to spend two or three hours together getting our rocks off (once a week?/month?/year? -- it all depends...). i can have this kind of relationship pretty easily. it does require great sexual chemistry and zero drama.

yes, a relationship can start as any of the above and transition to either of the other possibilities.

essay0:
(i apologize for the length of this summary, i sometimes over explain things and just couldn't leave anything out)
"and in the end, the love you take is equal to the love you make"
the above line is my favorite quote of all time because it's how i try and live my life. while i'm far from perfect, it's an ideal that i strive for.
i'm a college graduate with a history major and i'm trying to find my way in life. i currently work part time (but usually get full time hours) in retail, but am looking for bigger and better things.
i've lived in the bay area for just over a year now and have enjoyed my time up here so far.
people generally think of me as a nice guy (i've been accused of being too nice by some). i tend not to take myself too seriously. i've got a good sense of humor and can be sarcastic when the occasion calls for it.
i'm honest and fairly straight forward. i can be loyal to a fault. i'm a bit of a hopeless romantic, chivalrous, generous and look to help others when possible. i'm fairly laid back and am not quick to anger.
when you first meet me, i will come off as a shy guy, but once i get to know someone, i open up a lot and go from being an introvert to a bit of an extrovert.
i've also been accused of being a smartass, which i tend to agree with, i do think that my behind is quite brilliant.
i love animals, but i'm definitely a dog person. i do like cats, however, i am allergic to some.
i'm a hard worker and hate to be late, but i also love to kick back.
i'm a geek, and enjoy sci-fi and fantasy, with the original star wars trilogy being my favorite movies (followed very closely by the princess bride). i'm a gamer and enjoy playing with others as well as alone. i also enjoy reading comics.
i'm a bit of an oddity, i was born and raised in socal, and am about as much of a hardcore hockey fan as you can find (and no, my family isn't canadian). the anaheim ducks are my favorite team, but i'll watch any team play if i have the time, hockey is just an amazing sport to watch. i'm also incredibly excited that the echl will be moving a hockey team to san francisco starting next season!
i love to read, and lose countless hours of sleep to it every week.
i enjoy playing ultimate frisbee and soccer, but i haven't played much of either one lately. i'm always up for tossing a disc around with a friend.
i enjoy going to movies, and get groups together to go to midnight showings whenever possible.
there are times when i enjoy the company of an animal (usually a dog, but cats and others sometimes as well) more than the company of a person. this happens for 1 of 2 reasons. first of all, i communicate well with dogs and most tend to really like me. second, when i'm really down, there are few things that bring a smile back to my face like when i'm playing with a dog.
for you movie and tv fans, there are a few characters that i identify with decently to fairly well. they range from luke to mal to simon to castle to westley to perrin (bonus points if you know who every single one of these characters are). basically, a couple of farmboys combined with a difficulty in talking to girls combined with a hopeless romantic combined with an odd sense of honor and loyalty.

i moved to sf from ohio to pursue a masters in opera/vocal performance. once here i fell in love with sf and haven't left. i still love to sing, but pay my bills by working as a project manager at a start-up in palo alto. i also enjoy working part time as a music librarian. despite being in the city for over 6 years, i still love to play "tourist" and explore the city in search of new spots and new things i haven't tried. i'd love to hear about your favorite hidden gem in the city.

one major appeal to sf, is everyone leading active lifestyles. last year my roommates inspired me to start running, and last february i completed my first half marathon. now i've got the running bug and am currently training for a 50k. i stay active by running, hiking, rock-climbing, golfing, pilates, yoga, and am interested in getting a road bike. i try and take good care of myself by eating healthy, juicing fruits and veggies, and having fun exercising, but i'm not the type to deprive myself of the occasional burger, sweet treat, or cocktail.

i'm the youngest of 3, but am often told i act like a first born, whatever that means. as a child i was exposed to lots of different people and experiences. from my dad i learned the value of hard work and integrity, and from my mom i inherited creativity, spontaneity, and my love for baking. my parents thought it important that we always try new things, and so i grew up playing multiple sports, practicing multiple instruments, taking a variety of art classes, and traveling to a variety of places. i feel lucky to have visited half the 50 states, 3 provences in canada, france, italy, belgium, austria, germany, spain, italy, the dominican republic, and most recently haiti.

i love to travel! i'm fascinated by other cultures and while i always enjoy the whirl wind vacation seeing as much as possible in a short span of time, i also love picking one place and immersing myself in the town and its people. as a singer i studied french, german, italian and a little czech. before a recent work trip to haiti, i taught myself creole.

i consider myself to be very easy going and open minded. i am an eternal optimistic, always looking on the bright side. although some call that naive, i'm fully aware of life's realities, but it requires less energy to laugh than it does to complain. at the end of the day i'm open to life's possibilities and choose not to stress about the future, but rather appreciate the moment.

...if you've read this far and want to know more feel free to contact me.

back in the bay after a long hiatus.

i tend not to like to summarize, as a i really dislike being typecast. i'm happiest when i'm learning, and have really broad interests--it's always a struggle to find balance and fulfillment among intellectual/idealistic/artistic/athletic pursuits. my academic interests have tended to involve international studies (law/politics/econ), but also international lit.

but i'm pretty content to be in the bay these days. i'm pretty well traveled, at least in the western hemisphere. have studied and lived abroad in various places--budapest/chile/buenos aires.

i'd like to think of myself as pretty humble and fair-minded, but i also enjoy arguing a bit. rest assured that it's nothing personal. my friends inevitably tend to have strong opinions and relate to the world intellectually--they are creative lawyer types, scientists, artists.

sense of humor is deadpan, with absurd highlights and a smidge of snark--but only when you have it coming ;)

i'm generally suspicious of archetypes, but if infj means anything attractive to you, then perhaps i'm your huckleberry.

in my free time, i like to get down, play capoeira, and watch an occasional soccer game. i spend a lot of time hiking in the east bay's regional parks with my pup, and love backpacking.

essay0:
hi....

i am an expat living in san francisco for the last 8 years. before then i lived in england for 8 years and before then was in scotland where i was born. i spent a few months in bolivia after college too. all and all i am pretty aware of what is going on in the world today and am interested in people who are interested in the world, not just with what is going on in this land.

i have a good life with great friends, a great home, a great job and i am healthy. i am a happy guy and am both light hearted and thoughtful. i have a strong set of values which include hard work, discipline, sacrifice, love, family, education, trust, nature, active listening, humbleness, intellectual curiosity, honesty, laughter and joy, spirituality and passion.

while i am always open to new friends, i am really looking for a new best friend, partner and lover. i am looking for someone who shares many of my values but also compliments those with their own special values.

certain of my values definitely come from my upbringing in scotland. while my life is balanced here, with the right partner and plan, i would be up for exploring more of this amazing earth on a short or long-term basis. my new partner will definitely appreciate european ways (other than the accent)......hopefully you know what that means!

love and laughter!
essay1:
in my days i work at my career in real estate. i am a senior professional at a respected company and really enjoy what i do. that job gives me financial stability which takes off much pressure in my life. i own and live in a lovely non-conventional condo in mission bay (more artistic than cookie-cutter) and i have plenty of vacation allowance to use up each year. i really do leave my work at the door and spend the rest of my time checking out new places to eat in sf, acting the fool and being playful, taking in movies, occasional but not enough live theater hanging with friends, inventing and doing random creative projects, enjoying parks in sf during the summer, hitting music festivals, finding remote natural hot tubs, camping, drinking whisky (scottish) and wine too much or not enough, hiking and more. i love getting in the car and hitting the road!

keeping fit and being active is very important to me for many reasons. i go through phases of what i do.......yoga, pilates, gyrotonics, swimming.....and most so rolling around on my exercise ball while watching soccer in the mornings. i used to rock climb and run more, and perhaps one day will again. paddle boarding is something i want to try in 2012. first goal is to work on healing up an achilles tendon injury....more ultrasound and ice please, doctor! so frustrating.......but i must be zen.

working on the spiritual side of life and my heart are have been a focus for the last 5 years. i ain't no hippie and i was born with a cynical streak, but i am open to new things and pursue them with more regularity these days. i make an annual pilgrimage to meet a native indian in arizon and walk into the desert after eating his special cactus and i go to a meditation thingie twice a week. these things help me stay in the present and trust that all will be ok!

other than that, i am now looking at real estate investment opportunities in the inner mission with a friend. that is a hobby that is fun and fruitful (i hope). i am also working to promote electric bicycles in the bay area (www.yubaride.com), and as of this week now helping out a friend on their initiative to build a cacao farm in hawaii....did you know that kuaii is the only place in america you can grow cacao and thus make american-made chocolate?

i moved to san francisco in fall of 2010 from petoskey, mi. i love both places and live in sf, but spend as many weeks of the summer as possible in the traverse city/ petoskey, michigan region. summers are for swimming and floating (preferably all day), and sun-setting (still haven't seen more than one/ day), and niece-throwing (into a lake, geez!), and bonfires (be certain to keep the nieces out of those).

i'm athletic when presented with a sport, but i'm a klutz in my daily life. i was once bought a sippy cup because i am prone to knocking over the glasses of water i leave everywhere, and would do well to replace it. i'm definitely adventurous, both domestically and out-of-doors. i probably own too many shoes, but not enough camera lenses. anyone want to trade?

i love easily and consider myself passionate - for a ratiocinative, anyway:). my politics are quite left of center. i've been described as having a logical mind, but i hold emotional intelligence and compassion in higher esteem. i find the most interesting colors intermingled with thoughtful shades of gray.
essay1:
helping under-served people with whatever gifts i've been given, changing careers, spending time with the people i love. i moved to san francisco because i enjoyed it immensely when visiting, and my life in michigan was ripe for change.

i used to play the sax and coach volleyball, but most of the past 10 years of my work life have been dedicated to mental health social work. i have an mba with an emphasis on nonprofit management (undergrad in psych), and i currently work with teens who have disabilities and behavioral issues. my teaching certification is next on the list, and i hope to have my own classroom sometime in the next two years.

romantically: partnership is a truly lovely thing to have, but i feel complete with or without it. i'm ready - and looking forward to - falling in love again, but do not want to try to fit dating partners into a preconceived mold. let's meet and move forward from there. i've found kindness and honesty to be the best guides when shaping relationships, and have no interest in dating people who have trouble practicing both. if you need to compartmentalize your relationships and loves, please work that out before contacting me :).

i also love hands and climbing trees and singers who laugh in the middle of their lyrics because they still feel the same way they felt when they wrote it. i hope that when i look back on what i've created, i can always still feel what i felt when i wrote it.

essay1:
i'm a photographer interested in decay, details, surrealist portraiture and cultural enclaves. i travel as often as possible -- my role model is my grandmother, who has been to every continent (even antarctica!). i'm studying languages with the goal of one day being fluent in at least five. i love meeting people from around the world and exploring new places through food, language, and terrain. i want to swim in as many bodies of water as possible.

i'm currently two-step dancing, cooking chinese soup, playing soccer, reading zines, studying italian, and learning to do calligraphy.

essay4:
a) beautiful and insightful books, please. i love to laugh. i enjoy outdated instructional manuals. jeanette winterson, james baldwin, miranda july, the god of small things, harry potter.

i love everything about books: the paper (rattlingly delicate and thin, or sturdy textured cream), the raised font on the cover (to run fingers over like braille), the way it falls open to a certain well-loved page. and markings, of course, underlinings and notations and photographs forgotten inside a book that hasn't been checked out of the library in nineteen years. i want to rescue those books and take them out in the world, hold them up in both hands, and swing them around in the sunshine.

b) i love going to the movies by myself and watching foreign dramas about lovers and fate and tragedy. i want to care so much that i can't sit still; i want to cry, i want to be changed. and then sometimes i just want a terrible movie made for preteen girls. specifically, mary-kate and ashley.

c) jonsi, the bird and the bee, bjork, metric, des ark, royksopp, imogen heap, jill scott, ludacris, basement jaxx, mew, all boy bands (even the bad ones). i need to be able to feel the groove, then get into the lyrics, then swoon into one part of it, then dance it out.

d) i am a gourmand. i will eat almost anything if it's prepared well. i especially love new mexican food, tofu, peanut sauce, avocados, steamed artichokes, persimmons, blood oranges, red wine, taco salads, fresh figs, my grandmother's late-summer tomato pie, good coffee, gelato, fresh ricotta and buffalo mozzarella, zucchini bread (my specialty), and anything infused with lavender. i love trying new foods and cooking new foods, and i put hot sauce on everything. the spicier the better.

i'm randal, an import from manchester/england to the shores of the pacific.

i've got to say, i'm not one for going on about myself, so writing this section is like chewing broken glass.

it has been said that i have a playful sense of humour (check that out - a 'u' in 'humor', how exotic!), sometimes a bit facetious, but having a laugh is my raison d'etre.

i'm an avid manchester city fan (they're an english foot-fuckin-ball team, for the ill-informed), and i must warn now, when anyone confuses the huge rivals that are manchester city and manchester united it is to me as kryptonite is to superman, or salt to a slug.

i like parentheses' and ellipsis'... actually, i just like to write in a style that encourages people read it in the way that i'd say it, with subtext (a bit weird?... no? makes me sound a bit like a control freak, but i'm quite the opposite).

if i start another paragraph with "i", "i'm", or "i've", i may drift off, so we'll move on to the next section...

..you've done well so far, you get top marks for reading all of this drivel, girl!

i've just reopened this account after ending a 9 month relationship. so i'm very slowly dipping my little toe into the dating pool. i think i'm window shopping, but i'm not ready to go into the store yet.

that said, a friendly cup of coffee where there is resonance may be a possibility, and who knows what the future holds?

at this point, i not only view a relationship in terms of what is given or received in the moment between the two people in question, but also in terms of what sort of effect is created in the world with the other person, through our connection - the bird's eye view, so to speak. this is what will remain in the end, after all.

i'm committing my life to personal integrity and being the best, strongest person i can be. i'm ultimately interested in building a connection with a person who shares those values. i would like to create through my connection with another person, a sense of inspiration and mutual support and encouragement. i would also like for our connection to have a the ability to provide an uplift to others we may interact with, as well as a sense of fun, joy, groundedness, compassion, celebration.

so what does this look like? i appreciate men who are are available, kind, dependable, consistent, and willing to do whatever it takes to communicate through the hard stuff, as well as show up for the fun and joy.

in return, i'm compassionate and kind, curious and respectful. i am comfortable with people being themselves. i find that i can be accepting of many things, provided that there is clear communication and respect underlying our interactions.

i believe in going slowly, and ultimately, i'm looking for a relationship of quality that evolves from honesty, compassion, and awareness.

i experience divinity in all things, and have little use for organized religion, aside from retreats, music events, or cultural activities. i'm not looking to date an atheist or agnostic, since we won't share a common language about something i consider quite core.

i'm intuitive, direct, balanced, and health-oriented. i'm deep and a goofball - i love to laugh. i'm a bit of a tomboyish music geek in the sense that when i jam with my guy friends, i am one of the guys. when i'm on a date with you, i'm all about looking to get my needs met as a woman. sound good? :)

if you are reasonable, like me, you'd see that the art of writing a self-summary is a struggle between being fully authentic while being self-promoting. life is like that, so what can you do but embrace it?

so some grippy bits about me: i qualify as a full-on geek, and therefore have a geeky approach to the things that i am into. my tastes are quirky and eclectic. my interestes are both in matters intellectual and puerile. i love music (live and recorded), building stuff and going along with friends to try something completely different. i like to explore the city by bike and and enjoy spontaneous occasions. i enjoy partaking in general mischief as a creative act: live it; love it; do it with heart.

ok, so full disclosure: i am happily married and we both enjoy seeing other people as part of our lifestyle. we are dedicated to each other but enjoy "extracurricular" relationships. while we do see women and couples together, i am on okc to meet like-minded women who are either poly, poly friendly, or at least ambivalent about this arrangement. since i am new to bringing this side of me to online dating, i don't have specific expectations as to where this will go. i hesitate to check the "casual sex" box because is really not what i am all about. i am looking for someone with whom i share a mutual "click" with and can quickly over that initial awkwardness about talk about teh sexy.

if you are still reading this, awesome. you got past the potentially awkward bit, so onward to more stuff!

gotta grab your attention! ok, i've been described as confident, comfortable, genuine, & an entertaining story-teller. i'm a social creature who enjoys learning what people are all about and how they arrived at where they are today. i'm mainly on this site for dating, but i've also made a handful of great friends too (yes, i do believe coed friendships can work). i'm looking for someone with interesting perspectives and positive attitudes towards life.

i've gone on many dates since moving to ca two years ago and have notice a reoccurring pattern with my dates:

- they are often surprised how comfortable i am at approaching & talking to women about any subject. this is mainly because of my upbringing but more on that later...

- i prefer to be tactfully honest and upfront - "real" so to speak. this is often appreciated but surprising apparently.

- even if we get along over email or the phone, that may not mean anything until we actually meet. this is one reason why i prefer to meet sooner rather than later.

- i'm more generous and romantic than the average joe. however, i only reserve this behavior for special people/occasions.

- i haven't had many bad dates, but those that were involved women who weren't open to friendship or upfront.

about my date:

i find that the more i date, the shorter my checklist of "requirements" becomes. every woman has her own strengths & charm, but ultimately i am simply looking for someone to share great chemistry and experiences.

what i am doing:

i'm an advocate of working hard to play hard. you can often find me trying new restaurants, going to art shows/festivals, playing pool with friends or challenging strangers, or going for a jog in the east bay.

random things i dislike:

eggplant - something about the texture; wind chill; snowboard whiplash; bugs the size of my fist - pretty disturbing; trying to get the last drops of a drink and having the ice fly into my face.

message/wink me if you're into great food, drinks, & conversation with depth.

i have a new york, smart-ass, sarcastic side to me, but i tend to use it for humor and not to put people down. think of a slightly less snarky jon stewart. politically, i'm very liberal, although i tend to get kind of miffed when people don't hold up their end of the social compact.

i'm comfortable hanging out at home, but i also like to socialize, to explore san francisco's cultural attractions, and to play outdoors. if i'm home, i might be reading, watching a movie or, if i'm good, working out. if i'm out socializing, i'm likelier to be in a restaurant or a coffee shop than in a bar. if i'm getting all cultural, i might be at a museum or the symphony or the theater. if i'm outdoors, i'm probably in the park or maybe doing a day hike or a weekend trip somewhere within driving distance. i love the water and for some reason have a thing for islands.

not 100% sure what i'm looking for in a relationship right now. not aiming to settle down immediately, though that's probably not terribly far off, and you never know when lightning will strike. basically interested in meeting a nice guy and seeing where it goes from there.

i just moved to san francisco after living for a few years in dc and nyc. so, recently been just taking it all in. sf is amazing. since i'm new to the area, thought it'd be fun to meet some new people.

i grew up having an amazing appreciation for good food & wine thanks to my mother "the chef" (i think thats why i read cookbooks for fun) and my motorcycle license thanks to my dad "unrequited rebel who does calc for fun" ... sort of turned out to be a well rounded kid i suppose. my family is highly entertaining; keeps me witty and laughing. at least i can say i look forward to our family trips. whether its saving my mother from drowning in a foot (yes 1) of water while we're snorkling in st. johns (i know, how on earth did she do that), trying to race my dad down the slopes during ski season, or making the youngest sister our dd while touring napa... we seem to always have a good time.

my friends describe me as genuine, with a self-depricating sense of humor which has always made for good stories. i'm laughing with you, while laughing at me.

if you had a bad day, i'll make you lemonade...and i'll spike it if you'd like. don't sweat the small stuff. i'm more optomistic than cynical. glass is half full kind of girl.

you can tell i'm nervous if i suddenly have a british accent.

despite the ever busy every day life, i always make it a point to stop and do something i love. i keep a well balanced life between work and play. i've been very blessed by the people i've met and the places i've seen, like most, i can't live w/o travel. you always find the most amazing, beautiful and awesome things in the most random places. see, taste, hear, be. it shapes you, molds you, creates you. i adhere to the saying "pay it forward." paying it forward is always key and i find it keeps life in check. i'm more of a get your hands dirty kind of girl. more action less talk. i spent last august in honduras building houses, fortunately my job lent me the ability to go m.i.a in order to do so.

besides the above, i like to kick it with friends, hop in a random class (sf is awesome in that regard), head outdoors, take a sunday drive, hop the ferry, cook for friends, relax or not relax, read, create, listen, hang with the fam, go to a giants game....etc etc etc

hey there. thanks for stopping by to check out my profile. so, hmmm...here's where i have to talk about myself huh? not an easy task to summarize yourself in a paragraph or two but i'll do my best. i consider myself to be a down-to-earth, honest, compassionate, balanced, playful and spiritual woman who loves life and loves to laugh. i'm ambitious, intuitive, adventurous and passionate about achieving my goals, and following my heart at all cost. i really do believe that all things are possible in this life and that it is only our beliefs that get in our way. i love to try new things and stretch my own boundaries. i'm just as comfortable roughing it while camping as i am with a night out on the town. i live simply and love the small, beautiful details of this life....smiles, good times spent with good friends, dogs, peanut butter, a warm night, a hot bath, silence, sleeping under the stars, the smell of rain, music in all forms, the warmth of sunlight.... i can be quite serious at times but also have a seriously silly (sometimes a downright smartass) side to me. i definitely like to play and have fun. i have always been a seeker of truth and absolutely love learning. i'm adventurous and am thrilled to try new things, travel to new places and discover other cultures and the stories of other people. i'm comfortable with all types of people. diversity is beautiful and there is something to learn, and something to give, to everyone we meet. i have a variety of interests, including reading, singing, making music, going to concerts, writing, dancing, firewalking, the study of metaphysics, healing, massage, skydiving, trying new things, traveling, etc. but my greatest addiction is music. my favorite music is pretty much anything with good groove...funk, jazz, soul/neo-soul, etc. music is oxygen for the soul. truly.

ideally, i'm looking for "my lobster"....someone who is my best friend, the person i love spending time with most, someone who makes me laugh, makes me think, encourages my growth and enhances my talents. someone who is genuine, authentically himself, comfortable and confident. someone who is spiritually motivated, whatever his path may be that brings him closer to his creator. someone who is down for the adventure and can spontaneously and boldly pick up and go where his path leads him. someone who values and honors the things in life that truly matter.....love, family, friends, assisting our fellow human beings, etc. and above all else, i'm looking for that undeniable, indescribable chemistry.

i'm also down to meet great people and hopefully make some good new friends as well. so if that's all it becomes, that's totally cool with me. good friends are just as valuable as a great lover. so, if any of this resonates with you, then hit me up and let's see where it goes.

so here's the thing: although i'd love to find and make a real connection with someone, dating itself can become a full-time job. and when you're busy with other things -- such as an active, productive, offline life -- it can start to feel like a rat-race and stop being fun. and that's no good. in the meantime, i continue to have needs and desires of my own, along with the ample ability (and the strong, strong desire) to satisfy the needs and wants of a like-minded woman.

i'm looking for a smart, kind, confident woman who also has a naughty side. the kind of woman that no one would suspect would be bad, but underneath it all, she has needs of her own, and she needs to satisfy them, ravenously. looks matter a great deal, obviously, but i find hidden naughtiness to be an incredible turn-on, perhaps because i prefer to keep my own naughtiness firmly in check, only unleashing it around a select few.

this is all something of an experiment. what follows is completely honest and legit, but it's just one, very private side of my personality. the experiment, then, is to see what happens when i stop being private and start being direct (like "the real world"!). although i'm being very up-front about things, i hope you can detect my playful tone. i also hope you can detect that i'm more than just your normal sleazy guy looking to get laid -- i'm educated, accomplished, happy, and i have a wide range of non-sex related, non-online related interests and pursuits. i'm also quite modest, too :)

why the dearth of pictures, you ask? because the bay area's a small place, and i know people on this site. i have no qualms whatsoever about being here. but i'm not particularly interested in friends, family, and co-workers seeing this private side of my personality -- that's all. i have absolutely nothing to hide, and if we hit it off and you're genuinely interested (and not just idly curious), i'd be more than happy to send you additional pictures.

i know that if a woman was in a similar situation and created a similar profile, she would be inundated with messages. if a guy does the same, what happens? we'll see ...

hm... myself. well i've never been a fan of writing about myself i just don't think i can capture the essence of me, just not objective enough. i will try to make a stab at this.

i am that guy that seems to know everyone, i like being able to know a lot of people. so many stories you can learn from just one person; however, i am in reality an introvert. i much prefer to recharge my batteries by hanging out in my house reading a good book, or in a coffee shop talking with a small group of friends.

i will say; however, that several of my friends and an ex of mine have called me a "food, espresso, wine" snob. i believe it's due to same reason someone said i was "precise". mostly not that i like the nicest things in this world, but because i expect a level of precision, i am very much my myers briggs type when you get to know me (intj). you just have to get past the illusion of social farced.

something else that i have been called before is, "dispassionately compassionate." what this means i am not sure but most people seem to agree with it. my only guess is that i am rather logical, but have a warm heart when it comes to people that come in to my life, even if it is only for a short time i still care about the people around me. i also am a firm believer in ""act only according to that maxim by which you can at the same time will that it should become a universal law."
now, if you really want to learn more about me or to get to know me outside of what i say, just email and or im me.

i was married for 20 years, i have been a widower since 2004, time heals all wounds they say, i do get a twinge now and again. i know how to make a relationship work. the theme of love is something that is important in the work that i create. yet there is also a sensual and sexual quality there also, not overt but tasteful. i am quite athletic- i really don't like to exercise and force myself to go swimming
weekly- and even do 16 laps of butterfly in my routine, i tell myself its good for the posture, plus it makes the hour go faster. i am mostly a vegetarian but do eat a little fish now and then , i was macrobiotic for many years, andmaybe still am a bit, i could cook you a dinner sometime. it is pretty clean and simple food .i do make a great flatbread and learning to make crackers for the crunch vs potato chips once to often. i do have a sweet tooth, i love milk chocolate as a favorite along with a pastry and latte, though i have to keep that to a minimum. the body is a temple a sacred vessel. what you do and put into it makes a difference for health and clear thinking. i should add that i eat some form of kale almost everyday. i am not a total bore, i do go out to eat once in a while, enjoy italian food and a sunday omelet brunch. i do like to be in the forest among the big redwoods, it grounds me since i am a little in the clouds. since i mentioned clouds, and my head, as an artist, i have done research into the spiritual sciences, seeking that great creative font, where all things come from. the well is indeed deep, which can be awe inspiring yet very overwhelming for a simple soul. so from this perspective, all life is sacred, the earth is sacred, and until humanity respects that concept, we will continue down the road of despair and unhappiness. i myself have great hope in the long term, for this is what my art is truly about, the great hope and beauty that is attainable in all of us. it maybe far off in the distant future-- we are in for a wild ride. that is why a guy just wants to have a some fun. let's go hear some live music. it would be nice to meet someone that is creative and fun with a loving kind spirit, so we can inspire each other, to new levels in all the creative realms.
if this sound interesting i look forward to hearing from you,
all the best
doug

essay0:
i've been told that i'm a big, strong, handsome hunk... but then again whoever said that was in love :-). regardless, i am easygoing, attentive, honest and loyal. i'm also a good listener and a fair arbitrator- and when necessary can be tough as nails.

i think i have lived a very interesting life (so far). it sure seems that way to me. never been much of a dull moment, with one unexpected or unconventional experience after another. it's not always that i've sought such things, but once my path found a trajectory, events and synchronicities seemed to take on a life of their own. i have always been an inveterate risk-taker. it's not that i like danger (i'm actually rather quiet)- i'm just so damn curious.

i'm in a bit of a "settling down" phase these days- although what lies around the next corner remains a mystery. i've been a dad (still am), been married (more than once), had a successful career (still do), traveled a good bit (want to do more), and in general have achieved more (and seen/experienced more) than i ever thought i would or could. so, i am wondering... now what?
essay1:
i've noticed that some people feel the need to state that they "love their work but don't identify with it". as if who they are and what they do are completely separate. i'm not quite that way. what i do is integrated into who i am, and vice versa. and it works great. my life (and work) is about telling the truth... and about service to humankind (and the planet)... about exploring problems and solutions... about growth and integrity... and about evolving the human potential.

i'm a documentary filmmaker by trade, and as such have always been curious about to the various forces at play in the world. i've had many opportunities to explore interesting, sometimes challenging and sometimes exotic people, subjects and locales.

right now i'm reinventing my life a bit. exploring the edges, looking for where to land. seeking warmth and companionship- a partner and playmate. i've been spending some time off (big sur and hawaii), reflecting and seeing old friends. for the last 18 years, i've been very parent-oriented. now that my son is 18, i have some room to explore.

i'm an animal loving, book collecting, video game playing, anime watching, comic book reading, bay area native and lover of all things geek, who still loves the outdoors and being active -- so long as it doesn't require obscene amounts of running. i'm also a champion of love and justice, but that part's supposed to be a secret.

part cowgirl, part ninja and part gypsy. i work with dogs for a living, own and ride horses, and work part time on a ranch out in the middle of nowhere where i chase cows. i don't smoke or drink, but i am a major sweetaholic.

my passion is animal behavior. if you can't stand to talk about animals (especially dogs) for at least half an hour straight, you probably don't want to initiate any conversations with me. same applies if you aren't interested in dissecting the troups of mecha and magical girl genres, discussing why ff8 was the last great squareenix title, or debating over which publisher is better: marvel or dc (i'm a marvel girl, but if you like dc it's ok. i can convert you).

i also really like unicorns. really. it's almost unhealthy.
essay1:
i currently work with dogs as a trainer and handler. my aspiration is to continue to study animal behavior -- focusing on canines, but not exclusively -- and possibly train animals for film.

i'd like to bring back the types of animal films i grew up with (homeward bound, lassie, benji, black beauty, etc.), which are sadly being replaced by cgi. and i'd like to do it with rescue animals.

i'd love to work with exotics as well, focusing on rehabilitation and reintroduction.

i just started taking wing tsun classes and i'm totally in love with it! i will talk about it for hours..complete with gory, violent details.

any personality that can be described in a nutshell belongs there. that said, here's a few snapshots.

i am patient and unrelenting as the tides, which might be the same thing as saying i'm in my last year of grad school.

i love plots. no, seriously. i have a collection.

i grew up in a crushingly conservative and small-minded little town out in the deep desert. i escaped to college, and haven't been back since.

i'm data-driven and empirical. i have strong opinions, but i like to think i change my mind pretty quickly when i'm convinced i'm wrong.

i've been pointed squarely at a career in science since about the third grade, but not just because the world is amazing and full of fun surprises and deep puzzles. i believe strongly in the power of human reason to do good.

fairness is a big deal for me. i don't get angry very often, but watching one person exploit another usually does the trick.

when threatened by predators, i can inflate to three times my normal size.

i've been especially influenced by a few books. the ones that come to mind are guns, germs and steel; gdel escher bach; the making of the atomic bomb; and albion's seed.

dan simmons, china mieville, and neal stephenson usually don't disappoint me.

i'm a white queer cis lady livin' an workin' in oakland, ca. i think and yack a lot about white privilege and the various manifestations of sexism (e.g., hetero- and cis-), and how these show up in our everyday lives. i'm all about thoughtful language, stepping back, and constantly working to keep progressive movements accountable.

i identify as a feminist anti-racist ally, and i recognize there is a fuckton of privilege, racism, cissexism, ableism, and other things that need to be unpacked in each of these movements and claims. i'm big on being more active (not just opinionated) around these issues while sustaining my well-being. i fuck up a lot.

in things that are less serious bizness: i really really love languages (particularly russian and the maths), techno (more like techyes!), and whiskey neat. i think cats are totes the shit. lately i'll randomly shout "zero! zero fucks given! ah ah ah!" in the count's voice, then burst into uncontrollable giggles. and, indeed, i will not be bothered to give a fuck.

i am multisyllabic, heavily hyphenated, and nonetheless accessible.

i'm looking to meet people i know nothing about. i want to hear your story, what drives you, where you've been and the direction you're headed.

i'm 23, i've fulfilled all the graduating requirements for my bachelors degree and taking advanced painting as a final course (its a fantastic life choice). i'm up early in the morning trading stocks while others sleep in and begin their mechanical job from 9-5. i work smart financially, and hard physically. i play rugby and have an addiction for hard exercise. i used to be chubby with a bowl hair cut, cargo shorts and a baggy sweatshirt (i'm certain i sound perfect for you, and if you really want...i can go back to that image)

i heavily dislike the stereotype society has set up that i, being the male, need to contact you and say something fantastic that blow your mind with excitement without being bland, overbearing, rude, applesauce, cocky, disgusting, fire extinguisher, downright creepy or awkward.

you can message me, and i don't require much more than a "heyy" because i understand the difficulty in approach. i myself am a deer in headlights the first two minutes i meet someone, and after you swerve out of the way and crash into an nearby tree to save my life...i resume being an outgoing, interesting guy to meet.

regarding my "replies selectively"...that's a lie, i reply to everyone. feel confident and comfortable sending me a message, you'll get one in return

i decided to rewrite some of this since my original text makes me come off as somewhat pretentious and not really that nice.
so far i have lost a lot of money on drugs, but i have lost more money lending books to friends. i work in a kitchen, which means i curse a lot, hang out with jocks who make fun of how nerdy i am, and can drink many beers in a row. i now also work in the wine industry which despite it being a slimy amoral world, obsessed with a closed set of fundamentally useless knowledge and plagued with elitism does in fact have some negative parts. i grew up in oakland and as a result i am always conscious about things that may get stolen. sometimes books put me into the same state that people get into on cocaine, where i blow off my friends because i just want to read one more chapter, and one more and one more, and this will go on for hours. funny is the most important quality in friends. i am always surprised by how much of an impression visual art makes on me, agnes martin broke my heart a little bit. i used to go to boxing classes many hours a week and it left me with a certain jumpy anxiety that someone was going to hit me and make math way harder for the rest of my life. i try and take photographs as much as i can, right now i am really into portraits, which is some total photo 1 shit, but whatever i didn't go to art school i'm figuring out all this cliche stuff on my own. i don't really scar, but this is boring, i only wrote it down because staring at my face i realized there's no way to tell i broke my nose and reset it in a warehouse bathroom; i feel a little cheated that's all. i've spent the last few months teaching myself guitar from the hours of 1am to 4am. this should reveal two things 1. i am not very good 2. i am not a morning person. i am honestly about 9 years old inside and cynical as hell.

i dislike writing about myself but i suppose there is no real other way to come to any conclusion through the internet if two perfect strangers would have any sort of basis for a potentially life-altering encounter. for the most part, i am quite empathic and if you are too, we can have endless conversations without ever saying a word. however, i do value communication, a lot actually. especially the clear kind devoid of sarcasm, snarky comebacks, etc. i am for the most part, an optimist. and for the other part, a realist. so i'm looking for a relationship based on mutual growth. i'm equally comfortable being a teacher and a student as i've had practice being both for many years over. i like problem solving rather than philosophically pondering the nether reaches of obscurity. i'm not saying that everything needs to have an answer, but i like my philosophical thinking to lead to discoveries (those light-bulb moments) rather than to more unanswerable questions, if you catch my drift.

i generally like working on projects together, whether it be building something, or cooking dinner together. i enjoy collaboration. so it would be great to have activities with mutual interest. i've worked with horses, have sailed, like camping, play instruments, practiced various forms of art, etc, so try me. i'm not afraid of getting my hands dirty. i enjoy going out and socializing but also enjoy quiet time, and find that i need a good balance of both. i don't smoke or use drugs. not really a drinker of alcohol or coffee.

my familial roots are in japan although i'm chinese. and i grew up in the bay area. some people get this, other people just get confused. why? i have no idea....

summer is finally here. any excuse to go to the city, or camp, or hike somewhere is a welcome respite. i'm for the most part very laid back, would enjoy a night of laughing and jokes over serious talk. i like conversation a lot. activities are fun too. i'm also pretty self-deprecatory. sometimes people think i am fishing for compliments. that is almost always never the case.

before i came to stanford i was living in ecuador for two years, teaching and bumming around, traveling to peru the beach and cuba. before that i lived in new mexico in an isolated indian community for five years, teaching and roaming the desert. that was a pretty incredible experience, but many of my friends and family were a little worried about my decision making skills. it was pretty isolated.

in my free time i try to make it to the gym a few days a week, play soccer and spend time with friends. i like to spend my spring breaks camping somewhere (joshua tree being a favorite) and my weekends having a drink or watching a movie.

essay0:
i'm not really into self-promotion, so i'll share a story of how i recently celebrated my 34th birthday. my friend and i were tasked with a scavenger hunt all over le de la cit in paris in search of comt cheese, saucisson, and bien sr une baguette. our other friend would supply the wine and champagne. we met at the edge of the island, overlooking the seine. the sun began to set as we dined on meats, cheese, and wine on this most glorious autumn day in paris. it was truly memorable birthday, but most of all, it was better than celebrating at a mexican restaurant, wearing a giant sombrero.

hopefully, that story gives you a gleam into my personality. i love travelling, food, wine, and experiencing different cultures. i don't particularly enjoy tourist attractions. for me, travelling is my way to see the world through a different pair of eyes and realize there's more to life than my little corner of the planet. my other great passion is music. i've devoted an entire room in my house to be a music studio and to house my vinyl record collection.

career-wise, i reached a good amount of success at an early age, but i feel i sacrified some of my personal life during that time. now, i'd love to meet someone special and be in a relationship and eventually start a family. my first niece was just born a few months ago, and it's an amazing feeling when i hold her and look into her adorable face and can see some semblance of myself.

if you think your personality would complement mine, send me a message. i'd love to meet intelligent and interesting women.

southern gentleman born and raised in georgia, mostly greek by heritage. i moved out to the bay area a couple years back for a job and have loved being out here.

i was brought up to realize life is a continual learning experience, and thankfully it's something i happen to love. knowledge is a powerful force. this can present itself as me being nerdy/geeky, with a love of puzzle solving and games, which also happens to be the exact kind of thing i'd go for.

and i tend to have a drier, more cynical sense of humor. but really, i mock because i care.

also, i'm a ramblin', gamblin', helluva engineer.

just fyi: currently have a beard/moustache. i'll likely have it until i tire of maintaining it.

most of it now is working as a software engineer at a place i love.
my perfect work is what i do: take a problem, break it down, and solve it. even better, collaborating with others to find it. i'm a firm believer that anything i can do can be improved with the help of others.

otherwise either spending my time out with friends or as a homebody working on personal projects.

i would like at some point to get back into education, either taking classes or teaching, though i'm not ready for that at the moment.

essay0:
one of my fondest memories of sf: the night i made friends with three strangers, and two hours later found myself flying a stunt kite out of the back of a moving convertible, the wind blowing tears of laughter out of my eyes.

i keep a list in my wallet of the friendships i've made that started by going out on a limb, as a reminder.

the last week of my shoestring-budget backpacking trip, my grandparents transferred some cash so i could spend the night at a nice hotel. i thanked them and secretly used the money to go skydiving over the swiss alps.

the places i've felt most at home: grilling meat by the pool on a sunny day. revising short stories among the mission-style buildings of stanford and santa clara university. kicking it with the locals at my neighborhood bar in sf. sleeping in a hammock on a remote beach, with no idea what country i'll be in two days from now. and lately... dangling from a cliff.

in my first attempt at a profile, i sit here dumbfounded, scratching my head, then proceed with the soon-to-be incongruous and barely intelligible assemblance of thoughts and descriptions.
yup, that would be me.

im quite sure this one will end up in the circular file for a rewrite, but, um...here we go

gotta say, i really don't much like talking about myself. east coast, then transbay transplant that's planted here now for 30 years or so. tried to leave a couple times, but i missed being pushed from behind by miniscule ancient chinese ladies barking in cantonese while waiting in line in the bank. i mean, who wouldn't miss that?
and besides, i was busy daydreaming while my turn awaited.

life has definitely been a myriad of experiences. never thought i'd be who i am, or where i am. i always thought i'd be a famous artist, musician, or photojournalist. now i realize its not the fame. ego played a cruel game in order to motivate interests that would later become true appreciation. i thrive on being with the creative and humorous.

spend a little time wondering where the hell we're headed, watching things spin out of control, i suppose it's that way for everyone growing. i don't want to spend all my time on the phone.
sure, iphones are phat an all dat, but so is a good game of baseball or basketball, and it's difficult to hold the phone and play. (i have, however been known to light up a cigarette with tennis racquet in hand)

i've definitely spent too much time alone of late, so i guess it's time to get moving again. meeting new people. making new friends. opening up fresh experiences.

more later, im sure this profile stuff is a work in progress. who knows, maybe i'll win the lottery (i doubt it without a ticket), and end up in bahia, running an internet business on the beach, from a laptop, and, of course...updating my profile.

i moved to oakland about a year ago. for me, it was a big improvement over sacramento. i don't know if i'll ever truly become a "californian" - my east coast roots run deep - but am at least trying to enjoy things here while i can. this occasionally involves smiling randomly as i walk over to piedmont avenue or head out to buy fresh herbs, greens, and other assorted goodness (including the best creamy sorbet i've ever had) at the temescal farmer's market.

i watch the leaves sway in the breeze. i'm often astonished by the verdant nature of this place. even in winter! while friends back home in massachusettswere shivering their respective asses off nov.-feb., i was often able to have my windows open. damn.

i'm a bay area native- born in sf and grew up in berkeley. i went to undergrad in southern california and lived in la for a few years after college. i moved back to the bay for grad school in 2001 and since being back, make an effort to always take advantage of all the amazing places and activities that are close by- tahoe, yosemite, napa, giants games, nights in the city, etc,. i love to travel- i've been to europe a few times, mexico and hawaii a number of times, all over the u.s., and costa rica most recently. i played baseball in college and am still very active; health and fitness is a big part of my lifestyle in general, and i've also recently started playing on a few teams. i also coach a little league team, which has been a rewarding experience. in general, i'm pretty easy-going, make an effort to always keep a good work/life balance, love adventure and spontaneity, while at the same time can really appreciate a relaxing night on the couch with a glass (or bottle) of wine ;) i also love live music- i've seen some amazing concerts over the last few years.

i would love to meet someone who is intelligent, fun, successful, beautiful; someone pretty spectacular. i'm a little skeptical about the whole "online thing" in general, but i have met a few cool people and have heard the success stories, so i'm optimistic. i'll be happy just to meet and spend time with someone fun and just see where it goes- no big expectations.

oh, and ps- since it seems to be confusing to some people out there, i'm actually not a douche bag ;) (the ones i come across don't seem to know they're d-bags, much less be willing to admit they are one...)

hi, i'm ian. i'm here to find a sharp wit and a teasing, crooked smile. also true love and atlantis, but i'm keeping my priorities straight.

i need a steady supply of banter and flirting in my life. it's like verbal tennis - just sitting there hitting the ball is bland. it's when the other person keeps hitting it back that things can get all sweaty. we can go anywhere with each other, and have fun stuck in traffic on the way there.

challenge me intellectually, too. i didn't stop educating myself when it stopped costing me money. i like people with breadth, who put effort into finding the right answers to their questions, and who aren't threatened by disagreement.

these days i'm most interested in why we do the fucked up things we do. psychology, social science, politics. ugh, politics. why our insides make us so fascinating and exasperating on the outside.

when i was a little kid i played with lego, turned over rocks, and pulled the pigtails of the girls i liked. that kid grew up but stayed the same.

12/31/2009: i have been dilatory in not updating my profile. please accept my apologies. i am not available now. i have a new sweetie and she has two kids (the youngest of which is 15 mos) and i'm ecstatic (and also why i have not been on this site so much). so i am not available for other than friendships for the foreseeable future. i am poly, i know, but she is not and i am fine with that. honestly, i was having a hard enough time finding one sweetheart, let alone, more than one!

my intention in using ahava-rabah, which for those who do not know is hebrew, was to mean "unending love." some israeli acquaintances on this site have taken time to inform me that it really means "much" or "a lot" of love or "great love." so unending love is "ahava lo nigmeret." that is me.

i am a jew. my background is working class. i'm a self-employed financial planner and specialize in socially responsible investing. i started my business in 2002. it is going exceedingly well and i am having a great time. i love my clients. some of them even love me :-)

i have had lots of careers including in construction, art, organic farming, management, auto and motorcycle (still ride '75 honda 550k) mechanics, (still into old cars and i have a 1966 corvair hot rod - not too green). in the fall of 2006 son and i drove 3000 miles on a trip to colorado and new mexico.

i'm on great terms with my son's mother), and most (but not all) of my former lovers. i want to be a part of/create a family whose members supports each other to be and do what is most important to each of us in the world.

i believe in and make deep commitments. i love children and would like more or to participate in raising some more. i am a dad with a track record!

i am very sensual, love food (and cooking, mostly organics), film, literature, science, old cars (not in that order). i am pretty political and actively work to eliminate racism and other "isms" in myself and to interrupt them where/when there is a good chance it will make a difference (which is most of the time).

life is one big learning opportunity. i am a perpetual student of my own mistakes as well as my successes. learning new things never ceases to entertain me. ok maybe not so much the lessons learned the hard way- but we're all a work in process right? i am recovering work-aholic. i have learned there is more to life than what you do. now i'm working to find solid balance in most corners of my life. i understand the importance of a career & a comfortable living; the trick is to find the sweet spot in the middle. i am a firm believer that pets are part of the family. i come with a whole cast of characters including a dog and cat. two firm disclaimers; the dog will take a long time to win over and the allergic/ocd need not respond as the pets and (their hair) are a packaged deal. but if you can put up with them, it means you are probably pretty special.
other things i believe: laughter is the best medicine. you can teach an old dog, new tricks. if you volunteer, you will learn about yourself and others. yosemite is amazing & redwood trees are a treasure. saying thank you is important. everyone should know how to change a tire. dinner, a glass of wine and great conversation is underrated. i should go to the gym way more than i do. i want kids but not unless it's with the right person. i feel like a better person when i do yoga. communication is the key. i believe in one complementing the other; figuratively & literally. i believe in teamwork, working together, laughing together & growing together.
i am trying to meet someone closer to being on the page that i am on. ultimately i am looking to date someone who is fun to be around. i love funny guys who can tell great story & make me laugh. confidence and humor is so sexy! the guy i want to spend my time with is comfortable with himself with his own healthy balance, is best friend material, someone you want to spend the long term with. someone i can be honest and open with, laugh with, talk to for hours but is evolving. we are all a work in process right? it's a little chemistry, attraction, a lot of building a solid relationship & fun. so what do we have to lose?

essay1:
i am an artist, performer and teacher. a puppeteer by trade. i have had the great fortune to learn my craft as an apprentice working with a master of his craft. i wish everyone could learn this way. i mean... i love my teacher. not only has he guided me through creative processes but through personal ones as well. it makes me feel i am part of something larger than myself and that i am carrying on a piece of an ancient art form.

as a result, i feel a responsibility to pass on knowledge in this way and now have a few students of my own. there is nothing quite like seeing "the look" on a student's face when you see that they understand something new to them. it's very rewarding.

in addition to teaching, i perform semi-regularly for different companies and am hard at work building some pieces for my own company. my grand plan is to open a puppetry center in the east bay so that i can bring this wonderful art form to the community that i love.

mae west's mantra, you only live once, but if you do it right, once is enough is one i've adopted. fortunately, there are a plethora of things to be involved in and passionate about while on this great adventure. i'm trying to fit them all in. yes, right now. some of my passions: social justice, food justice, youth work, traveling, making a combination of those a reality with today's teens in public schools, theater (i love watching it, i'm not an actress), swimming, and ice cream. (balance is important, afterall!) if you don't think "ice cream" is something to be passionate about, there is much left for you to learn... and i look forward to introducing you to my favorite gelato places.

i have a zeal for learning and a sick love for discussing politics, or more accurately, political possibilities. the occupy wall street / oakland/ everywhere movement excites me. on the political spectrum, my friends would call me a progressive lefty.

i'm not counter-culture though. i don't have any tatoos and i have no plans to rename myself after any plants or geological features.

i am thoughtful, involved in my world, and empathetic.
essay1:
i teach high school and love it!

before i was so involved with that, i was over-committed to too many people and causes... and i probably will continue to live like this forever. if you are okay with that, write me. if you expect to be the sole center of my universe and that i will drop other responsibilities, that will probably not happen and i will resent you for even suggesting it. just sayin...

that being said, i make room for people who are important to me.

i'm currently in a long distance relationship with a wonderful person another state away. so i'm only looking for a dance partner, a movie friend, more pal-level folks to meet and hang out with right now. really.

essay0:
i always find these "describe yourself" things so awkward. it seems like there's no way to write it all out without coming across as either arrogant or insane. that's just because a simple text blurb is, frankly, no way to get to know a person. nothing can substitute for the little things in getting to know one another. texting each other every day, or lounging around on the couch doing nothing in particular but loving each second of it. anyways, i'm starting to ramble already, so i'll lay down a few basic facts about myself and then hopefully, if you're interested, we can find out what each other is really like by chatting some more.

i can confirm that first and foremost i am a hopeless romantic. even when the odds are telling me that love won't work out, i have no choice but to hope with every fiber of my being that it will. it's in my nature. that said, i try to be realistic about things even though my inner romantic may say otherwise. it... doesn't always work out.

i can also say for certain that i will probably act like a complete idiot when meeting you in person for the first time. i'm not great with meeting people, but i really enjoy the time that i spend with them after clearing that initial hurdle. i can be shy or a bit dry when meeting up at first, but that's just because i like to take my time and size up a person before really digging in to the relationship. if it helps, i've been told i'm hilarious by people who i've known for a long time.

i work for a small video game journalism website. what that means, essentially, is that i critique new video games, keep a blog of the latest news, and occasionally go to events or conventions like comic con or pax up in seattle. for the uninitiated, think of it kind of like a movie critic, but for games. i realize that claiming to be so deeply invested in the video game business tends to paint a very specific picture of me, but it's one that is largely inaccurate. i may fumble in early social interactions, but i also find that many of the people in the industry are just a little (or sometimes, a lot) too "nerdy" for me. don't get me wrong, i love nerdy girls, but to an extent. i really occupy a weird middle ground between huge nerd and average joe. i'm down for a game of magic or some xbox, but i can't do that stuff for extended periods. i need to get out and go hiking or walking or something too.

oh, and i don't really drink. it's not that i never have (ironically enough, i never have since turning 21) or that i have something against it, but i just don't understand why i would. downing some foul-tasting drink just to lower my iq doesn't sound like a ton of fun, unless we're all going to be sitting around playing cards against humanity or kinect all night. going hand in hand with that, i don't like clubbing much either. i know, i'm a real stick in the mud.

anyways, that's me in a nutshell. i don't want to keep this going for too long, but if you're at all curious i can at the very least promise you'll get some humor out of my idiotic attempts at socializing with you. that's sarcasm. hopefully.

edit: one more thing i left out earlier. i'm new to the bay area of ca (i actually moved from maryland) so feel free to drop in and say hi even if you're just looking for someone to hang out with or are new to the area yourself, as i can never know too many people and right now i know like none >.<)

lifewise? i'm treading water in the deep end of the swimming pool, avoiding the folks doing cannonballs off of the high-diving board. more simply, developing some concepts of happiness in a screwed up world. happiness is proportional to your humor. more humor, more happiness. it's ok to think seriously, but laughter sustains you through the serious stuff. happiness is not a box of chocolates, it's giving the chocolates.

j) textures -- marshmallow creme, soba noodles, crunchy fall leaves, granite, tapioca pudding, kitty fur (on a living cat, please), new socks

i'm a bit of an outsider and always have been. my obsession with computers, since the age of four, has guided most of my life. i was born in denver, moved to the rocky mountains, then a suburb of buffalo, then nefarious places in southern ontario canada, then just outside of toronto to go to the school i ended up dropping out of to move to san francisco and work as an ios developer.

since moving to san francisco, i've expended my horizons quite a bit. i'd not longer say technology is my primary interest, as i quickly learned that staring at a computer screen for upwards of eight hours a day can be rather dehumanizing.

despite my superego's petulant risk aversion, i'm a free spirit that is constantly seeking out a new experience. i love nature, music, reading, riding random muni lines, going out, films (especially indie documentaries), and art. i'm a morning person and i am constantly doing things. although, i do enjoy a good rainy day spent inside cuddling.

i love having a full gamut of people in my life. diversity is the spice of life, and there is so much to learn from people that view the world in a completely different way than you.

i love making people laugh and i don't take myself seriously enough to not self-deprecate (my life is too funny not too).

essay0:
i grew up in ohio and went to college in indiana. i moved out to cali right after school; unfortunately i lived in the south bay for a while (not a fan).

i've been in sf since 07 and absolutely love it! the culture, food, landscape, people... all amazing! my only complaint is the weather; i can only handle so many fifty degree days in the middle of july before i want to bust out of the fog and feel the sun on my face. but the winters make up for it. say it with me... tahoe!

disclaimer: i work in the tech/startup world, so i'm a bit of a nerd. i'm passionate about technology and have been bitten by the entrepreneurial bug. i started my own company but it crashed and burned in a blaze of glory that only people in this area can appreciate. so i'm back working for "the man", and i'm actually loving it. the company i work for feels more like a family. we eat breakfast, lunch and sometimes even dinner together. it's like a giant version of the brady bunch except we have 3 dogs and everyone can vote.

when i'm not nerding out i enjoy hiking, cooking with friends, drinking an entire bottle of wine (i can't seem to stop once the cork comes out), exploring this amazing city - pretty much anything that involves people and fun activities.
essay1:
you know those moments in life where you get clarity and wisdom that normally takes a lifetime to achieve? (if you said "no" i won't hold it against you) well i had one of those a few years back when i was at my first startup.

i was just out of college and became really good friends with one of the engineers who was in his early 60's; i'm hip to the elderly. he was going through a few really rough months - lost his younger brother and best friend - and was looking back on his life. he told me 1) when you're my age you won't regret the risks you took, you'll regret the risks you didn't take 2) if you ever find yourself bored with life, make a change 3) don't have any regrets.

his advice resonates in everything i do. my goal in life is to live it, take risks, have no regrets, and meet amazing people along the way. i added that last part because at the end of the day, people are what make life enjoyable. otherwise you'd be sitting around alone, and who would want to do that?!?

essay0:
[i was raised in a comedy club]

i find live standup comedy to be the most honest performance art. there is no backup band, dazzling visuals or understudy. its about one person, a mic and the desire to connect with audiences of varying drunkenness through laughter. forget the hack sessions you may have seen on cable tv, the recipe for winning over a live crowd acculturated to heckle you is: honesty. the mc's and feature acts with their rinse and repeat punchlines are working towards this. true masters of the craft share their unique perspective on the world with us. it may be exaggerated, cynical, dark, dirty, absurd, cerebral or silly... but if the crowd left in tears, it was an honesty shot to the heart, pulp fiction style.

maybe we should check out a show sometime?

[is foreign travel a ticket to ride on ok c?]

i've been around the world, too. i spent my high school summers doing exchanges, scholarship and work in europe. i've lived abroad in adulthood as well. (i speak german and have pleasantries in all the majors). after this exposure and rhythm, i surrendered any notion of national allegiance. i could be happy just about anywhere. in addition to shedding braincells but gaining inspiration throughout europe, i've spent time in asia, central america, islands, and a beautiful, often underrated zone called north america. in march i'll be headed to a place that legal council has recommended i not mention online. it rhymes with tuba.

do you want to meet for coffee at cafe international (haight and filmore) to exchange stories one weekend?

[everyone needs a creative outlet]

i write in spurts. it took me over a year to finish my book ("fictional exaggerations of reality", lulu, 2010). i find writing to be like flossing: sometimes its a chore to get started but i've never finished and thought to myself that it was a waste of time. to keep motivated, i started a little collective of bay area writers. if you can spend hours on vice "dos and don'ts", we'd love to have you.

after three sips of a good whisky, i'd be happy to read you some of my shorts. feel like meeting up for a drink?

hi, i'm toby, single guy and native east bay denizen. in some ways i am your typical guy, but in other ways i am not. how am i not, you ask? mostly it boils down to geekiness. i love nature, animals, the sciences, and somewhat ironically, science fiction. i also am quite affectionate.

i try to surround myself with what i love. i am a big train buff, so i got a job with a railroad. i am an animal lover, thus am currently at the beck and call of two cats. (i love dogs also, but don't want to subject one to apartment living.) i read about the sciences, and i hike (or kayak when the opportunity presents itself) to get back to nature. all i need now is someone to lavish affection on, thus this profile on okcupid.

i also like to travel, and have traveled a fair amount in my life thus far, but would like to do much more. i have traveled throughout the u.s. (have been to alaska, but not hawaii) and some of europe (germany, italy and france).

i like to give people a hard time. if you're on the receiving end, it probably means i actually like hanging out with you. some might say i can be a little too honest sometimes, but it's never out of malice.

to balance out the tough girl act, i also have a nurturing side. for instance, i've twice brought my friend's plant back from the brink of death. the first time she took it back, but the second time she let me keep it. i try to take equally good care of friends and family - except for the being near the brink of death part.

when i'm in the city i do a lot of the normal mission things like bike riding, rock climbing, checking out new restaurants and bars, and various modern homemaker crafting projects, but i'm also recently obsessed with backpacking and hope to spend some serious time in yosemite sometime soon. lake tahoe takes a close second as my favorite non-city place to be, in any season.

other things that occupy my brain at various times are the sf giants, science journalism, gardening, music, and the latest this american life podcast.
