essay0:
i had forgotten i had not filled out these sections and now i know why: it's not easy. i am more educated than i have ever needed to be, and have spent most of my working life traveling and working in the most esoteric of fields, and have loved it. my kids are mostly through college and their mother graciously lives on the east coast. liberal is a conservative way to describe my politics. i have moved seven time in the past ten years, but hope i am settled here for the foreseeable future. i read often, most recently "night train to lisbon: and "this is your brain on music." skiing is my most recent rediscovery. although i like the female presence in my life, i am not sure that it has to be just one for the rest of the journey. i appreciate the depth and value of a close personal connection, and usually find myself committed to the detriment of my sense of self expression. perhaps the right woman will ease my way through this?

i am generous to a fault, interesting, and open minded

now, i just don't get the one and only thing about seeking to meet someone online. i cannot imagine meeting someone with the intention that i am seeking to spend the rest of my life with them.
i think that would get in the way of relating naturally to each other. i have nothing against a good committed relationship, but to think this is it when i seek to meet someone here just does not connect to me. about the most i would want when i meet someone here is that i have a good enough time that i would want to meet again. and then next time, i would like the same, and if it continues like that then a truly involved relationship will develop, if that is where we both want it to go. yes, i have been known to not see it when it is there. you know ... smack on the forehead ... what was i thinking??? but i am not inclined to tell others what to do, and if your having fun, there is no need to push. what works for me is for each of us to be enjoying the moment for all that it is. the rest, whatever that may, be will follow from that.

and then there is ambition. what's that all that about? i have multiple graduate degrees, and have worked most of my working life in the most esoteric of fields and loved it, but i have never had any desire to win or reach some far off goal. i have no trouble deciding to do something and doing it, but it does not feel like ambition to me. i do not like to tell others what to do. managing others to me is working with them in a collaborative way, with each and every one welcome to contribute in their way. i have played sports like hockey and soccer, or tennis and squash, but rather than trying to beat the others, i usually feel that i am just developing skills that are fun to use. and it is fun, not conquest.

hmmm ... i guess that is part of the thing i realized after my most recent divorce. i have lived my life in a power struggle. it is time for that to end. relationship is not about a power struggle, someone has to lose. i have no desire for the person i am in relationship with to lose, and neither do i wish to lose. resolving differences does not have to be a win/lose matter. i will not be in another relationship that is a power struggle. in a former life i was an attorney, and then realized i do not like to fight. it took me a little longer to figure out the i do not like to fight in relationship either.

essay1:
i basically play video games for a living. no, that doesn't mean i'm wearing sweatpants right now while cradling a liter of soda on my stomach, it just means i'm living the dream of every american child, which i think very few can say is totally true for themselves. to avoid those terrible cliches you may have in your head about gamers i hit the gym several times a week. it also helps burn off the elaborate meals i love to spend hours cooking for myself and my friends. you think you know what a hamburger is? give me 2 hours and i will prove you wrong. i love being creative in the kitchen, especially when i have someone to share it with (tell me how good it is).

i am planning on getting my mba sometime in the future, but that future is now further on the horizon since i put down a pretty penny for the bmw i've wanted since i was a kid. it may sound pretentious, but dammit--i've been working since i was 16 and it felt good to treat myself to something i'd like to think i deserve.

essay0:
i am a classically trained professional opera singer with eclectic tastes & a wide variety of interests. while i would love to be in a romantic relationship, what must be present is connection, & that all-elusive & inexplicable chemistry. i am not interested in a casual intimate liaison, a fling, or an instant relationship. i seek what is real & natural- something that can only be revealed in it's own time. my interests include, but are not limited to, all types of music & the arts in general (particularly latin & classical music & art); natural health & healing; ontology; philosophy; yoga; & quiet explorations of inner & outer life.

i would best describe my style as "casual elegance"... even though i am a classical performing artist, i am very down-to-earth & appreciate all that life has to offer. good communication skills are essential, & i am an excellent communicator & very easy to talk to. i love to learn about & experience new things, am adventurous & very playful, & am highly intuitive: i listen, & lead with my heart.

i am non-denominationally spiritual, as well as non-religious.
i do not follow any one path, but believe, like jiddu krishnamurti, that "the truth is a pathless land." i keep my heart & soul open to find my truths wherever they may be.
it matters not to me what you call yourself, but how you live your life, how you treat others, & how true you are to your word.
also, i have little interest in politics, but within that realm, i am naturally liberal, & have always voted accordingly.

physical fitness is very important to me. i practice yoga, & am currently re-working my fitness routine to include cardio, pilates, & strength training. i eat an exceptionally healthy, life-affirming diet, with the emphasis on lots of fresh fruits & vegetables, nuts & seeds, & smaller portions of clean protein.
i rarely drink, do not smoke or use drugs, & i lead a relaxed but active present lifestyle.

i love being in majestic nature, especially where i can experience the wonderous elements, & observe flowers & animals in their natural environments. i seek balance, harmony & beauty in my life. i have also found myself, at this point in my life, being drawn more to places of quietude & to a less frenetic pace. but, while i very much enjoy & seek quiet reflective "down" time, sitting on a couch night after night watching tv would simply bore me to tears!!

i am vital & energetic, spontaneous & curious, intelligent & quirky, sensual & affectionate, funny yet serious, & extremely passionate about life.

the man i would like to meet is ultimately seeking a life partner. but, he also understands the exquisite wisdom in taking time, & letting true connection slowly reveal itself. he is whole & happy in & of himself, is beyond playing games, & desires to spend the second half of an exceptional & inspired life with one woman. highly intelligent, he is sweet, kind, romantic, fit, passionate, & sound of mind, body & spirit. he is also spontaneous, curious, open to new experiences, & has a willingness to play in my world & the vast rich world around us.

physical fitness & a healthy diet & lifestyle are an integral part of his life. an appreciation of classical music & the arts would be lovely, as well as the ability to enjoy life's simplest pleasures. he is down-to-earth, yet capable of elegance, with class & style, is an excellent conversationalist, & is as comfortable in the world of high art as in many other echelons of life: from opera gala to country paths or local cafes....

someone who really knows how to make me laugh... someone with whom the world becomes a larger place because of our union... someone who will be my confidant, my lover, & my companion...
& someone who will be my very best friend.

essay4:
i don't have a favorite book. i like to read about personal growth, natural health & philosophy, & books that move, touch, inspire, &/or educate me. i have a stack of about 8 books right now waiting to be read in my quiet time during the opera off season.

while i don't read books for escape & fun, movies are another story altogether. i love movies for total escapism, or ones that make me laugh out loud, & feel good. i don't care about the genre, really. what matters is that it is well done. what i don't care for are movies that are about crime, gangs, murder, drugs, torture, misery, etc...or that glorify ignorance & stupidity... we have the news for that!! ;)

music: my tastes are so very eclectic.
obviously, i love classical music of all types, but, you won't catch me sitting at home listening to opera all day, as that is my "job", & i usually just listen for education, & when i am studying.
i do adore & listen to much transcendental orchestral music, & solo classical instruments, such as spanish classical guitar (my favorite), piano, & harp.
i also adore many different types of latin music, & listen to that most of all, simply for pleasure: boleros, latin pop, the old-style trios, like "los panchos", mariachi, salsa, flamenco, tango, ...also brazilian samba & bossonova.
i listen to ambient, new age, & some world beat as well.

food: i am an adventurous eater, & love many different cuisines.
i eat very healthily, as naturally as possible & love simple foods in their natural states.
during the day, i tend to eat like a vegetarian, & with utter simplicity:
lots & lots of fresh raw fruits & vegetables, nuts, seeds & eggs.
but, i am not a vegetarian- i love steak & seafood & chicken & pork!
so at night, i eat a healthy & hearty but moderate meal.
if i snack afterwards it is usually on more fresh fruit.
oh, & dark chocolate: that is not food, it is therapy!!! :)
essay5:
beside the obvious things necessary to sustain life, there is little that i could not survive without...i believe in the resilience & adaptability of the human spirit. i also believe in simplicity.

that being said, what i cherish & value, & what i am most grateful for are:

my good health.
freedom.
a connection to something greater than myself.
love, love love- friends, family, nature, & the meaning of love itself.

essay0:
***apologies in advance if i don't get back to you in a reasonable amount of time. i have my hands full at the moment.***

tl;dr:
canadian. grad student. shy at first; an open book with time. easy-going (often to a fault). introspective. attentive. clever. affectionate. introvert who loves being around people. analytical. hedonistic. caring. feminist. accepting. non-monogamous. carnal. observant. loving. driven.

"this is the whole of the story and we might have left it at that had there not been profit and pleasure in the telling; and although there is plenty of space on a gravestone to contain, bound in moss, the abridged version of a man's life, detail is always welcome." - nabokov

i was born in toronto and raised in a suburb just outside of the city. despite the cookie-cutter houses, humdrum lifestyle, and my k-12 experience in catholic schools, i think i turned out to be a pretty reasonable and open-minded person. you, of course, can make that judgment for yourself.

so why am i here now? that's a long story best told in person. i'd love to hear your story too. i think the way people reflect on their lives and make sense of their path is utterly fascinating. we can learn so much by reflecting on our past and listening to other people's stories.

full disclosure: i'm in a long-term, long-distance, open relationship with twentyover200. he is an amazingly supportive human being, and i'm honored to have him as a partner. we've spent nine years growing and learning together, but circumstances (i.e., academic opportunities) have kept us apart for the last three. after a whole lot of conversation, negotiation, and personal reflection, we've reached the point that we're both comfortable exploring relationships with others. we've been doing this for a while now, and it's been a bumpy (but generally wonderful) ride. i have a distaste for labels (language is so imprecise!), so i hesitate to slap any on our relationship or what we're looking for. the bottom line, though, is that we like people. we like connecting with people in whatever ways feel right for everyone involved. send me a message and let's see where life takes us. though i like to keep busy, i will always make time for the people most important to me! :)
essay1:
school-wise:
i read a lot, write a lot, and think a lot. this gets balanced out by spending some of my week in schools with kids. i love that i get to wear many different 'hats' in any given week - it prevents me from getting bored and helps keep me engaged in life. i work best when i have many things on my plate.

outside of school:
i'm busily breaking my own preconceived notions of what i'm good at or capable of. i've always been a bit shy and am not great at small-talk, but have recently been meeting new people and am really enjoying all the positive interactions. bring it on, world!

i've been very focused on academics since arriving here, at the expense of some other aspects of my life. this year (and beyond), i want to truly enjoy what the bay area has to offer - new people, new places, new food, new ideas. over the last few months, i've taken up some new hobbies - sailing (being on the water is very calming and soothes my soul in a way that i don't completely understand), glassworking (very meditative), and ceramics/pottery (who doesn't love getting their hands messy with a big pile of clay?). i also love cooking, but only when i have someone to share the food with. if you have a hobby or activity that you want to share, please let me know!

essay6:
in order of frequency:

1) relationships. having semi-recently entered into the world of polyamory/open relationships/non-monogramy, i spend a good deal of my time thinking through my actions, words, and emotions (past, present, and future). i'm working hard at being mature, compassionate, communicative, ethical, and considerate to the people i'm dating, the people they're dating, and, more broadly, everyone in my life. this has led to more concentrated personal growth and self-discovery than anything else i've ever pursued.

2) what (and who) i want to be when i grow up. what (and who) i want to be tomorrow. what new hobbies to pursue. what activities and experiences to seek out. click here (start at page 15, "some significant learnings") for a sense of the principles by which i try to conduct myself in interpersonal relationships. carl rogers is a wise man.

3) the education system. mental health issues. supporting families in crisis. supporting children in crisis.

4) psychology, specifically mathematical cognition and related topics. nerd alert, right? my research interests fall into three domains: (a) how, over the course of early development, we come to understand the concept of number and build upon that to understand higher and more complicated mathematics. i spend a lot of time reading and thinking about some wicked-cool studies demonstrating "innate" math abilities in infancy and even in other species; (b) how gender influences self-efficacy in the domain of math ; (c) how a lack of vision and visual experience (i.e., blindness/visual impairment) affects a person's ability to access and understand mathematical concepts.

i'm a software consultant living and working in a noe valley condo. i'm really not materialistic, but i do acknowledge material needs and take care of them. i prefer to ponder the nature of life, the creative and the psychological.

ethnically i am of japanese and midwestern jewish american descent. i was not born in this country, and feel a bit of an outsider to this day.

i'm into inner work and self improvement. i usually have a creative project or two on hand: play, poetry, novel, music, etc. life itself is a creative endeavor.

my login is a baudrillard (old interest) reference, selected back when this site was something different. most people think of me as an intellectual, although technically i'd say anti-intellectual. that weird test where your personality is reduced to four letters tells me i am intj. or did it say chaotic good? maybe it was earth monkey. or number six.

my last big trip was a tour of switzerland, netherlands and denmark (and sweden - for 30 minutes). i think during my trip i spent the longest time at dulles airport, though...well it felt like an eternity. definitely the dulles airport ever.

i don't particular think a lot about the following - but ok, that sign you just passed said full snark ahead:

whether it's possible to find an authentic relationship on a site where people willingly reduce themselves to pat answers on set forms, and are matched based on multiple-choice questions answered possibly years ago.

why people from the east coast insist they have an "edge", and what is it they want me to believe about them based on this assertion. some people in the west coast have edges, too. we here just call them a**holes.

why so many people here try to cover all the bases, which just makes them sound unfocused and non-committal: "down-to-earth sophisticate", "love ingmar bergman and south park equally", etc. or how about those people who say things like "i love to go everywhere - from posh cocktail lounges to dive bars" (that's not everywhere, lady. you forgot your local chapter of aa.)

essay0:
recently, i woke up to the necessity of choosing what i would take in a fire. i dressed warmly, put all my journals and my laptop in a bag, then stood to consider what else should go. then the fire was put out.

one of my jobs is a mildly frustrating writing-related job, but it's still writing-related. one of my jobs is a great customer service job, but it's still service. i like 'em, but i'm still working on the job part of living here (more editing, less service); i moved here for other reasons.

i just moved to a new apt., so i've been in piecemeal-home improvement mode: dreaming up uses for the space, painting, scrubbing the bad, pre-existing paint job from the tile... i need to build some basic ones first, but i've been dreaming of slanted display shelves ( la melancholia) so i can have a changeable gallery of books.

looking through the first of the aforementioned journals, from an unexpectedly early age 10, i'm surprised when i find that i wanted to be an author. i remember my love of language and writing coming much later. a veterinarian, my 3rd choice (after a baffling "chemist"), is what i've always remembered wanting as a child to be. i apparently also thought o.j. was guilty, and my favorite show was "mcgiver."

i am perpetually, poorly, learning french. a few years in college, some fitful self-teaching, poor attempts at reading, and lots of french film have given me a basic grasp, but my memory is poor for vocab that isn't actively used, and the more complex syntax still trips me up. i sometimes enjoy an evening working my way through a (stanza or two, really, of a) poem with my oxford french/english, though, and comparing it to other translations, mallarm and roubaud of late.

since mention of origins seems obligatory here, i'll say that people are often surprised to learn i'm from mississippi, as i have no discernible accent. it only comes out in a few words ("ya'll," "fixin'"), or if i've just talked to my family. i miss mississippi's food and land, but san francisco's landscape is a surprisingly good approximation of mississippi's, weather excepting; the thickness of the foliage in golden gate park was one of many things i fell in love with on my first visit here. you can see that reaction to golden gate park in the last photo.
essay1:
i feel i've spent most of my life learning, but san francisco is
about doing, so i'm working on doing. i'm still learning, of
course, but trying to focus on the doing. it's one of the reasons i
moved here. i've been lucky enough to meet some fascinating and odd
people here to help me along. the typical answer to this question
is about work, though; and while i enjoy my work, it isn't "what
i'm doing with my life." it would be great to merge the
money-earning and the doing, but until i figure that out, i do my
money-earning as a writing coach in an online college's writing
center. i also work in a museum store and sometimes in a bookstore.
i'd like to do more of the latter. when i'm not working, i'm
reading books, looking at art, working with friends to brainstorm
and plan parties we can throw in interesting, unused or non-public
spaces, exploring the city, going to movies that's the stuff that
i'm "doing with my life." that and fantasizing about a phd in art
history. but i need to get bored with not being in school first,
and i've been plenty busy for that to not happen.

essay4:
this is a dangerous section. i have two degrees whose fundamental subjects are "thinking about why i like what i like." but rather than divulge my personal aesthetic philosophy (that's more of a third-date topic, no?), i'll just say, these are some artists/works/topics which i like/will always love/am recently interested in:

beckett, james merrill, peter handke, gabriel josipovici, marianne moore, proust, thoreau, yeats, william gaddis, edouard vuillard, matisse, clyfford still, david park, john baldessari, the books, schubert's winterreise, bach's cello concertos, rem, titian, tintoretto, paul celan, muriel spark, ivy compton-burnett, georges perec, classical greece, robert bresson, rw fassbinder, michael haneke, von trier, hans arp, alexander archipenko, and the list goes on... i've been watching a lot of wong kar-wai lately. the triple-feature at the castro cinched my desire to seek out everything by him, rather than just come across it when i do.

i like a lot of tv, too: community, nurse jackie, venture bros., himym, mad men, desperate housewives, weeds, six feet under. raising hope has been making me laugh lately.

as far as food goes, i really like foodi am from mississippii'm not picky, i like eating out, and i'll at least try most anything. i'm omnivorous, but i try to eat veggie-style at least as often as i don't. favorites are indian and sushi. i'm on a continual hunt for good southern food here. i still can't quite believe that the only good fried okra in the bay area comes from a vegan restaurant [edit: blue jay caf's otherwise disappointing-to-acceptable southern fare made the sublimity of its fried okra unexpected; sorry vegan okra, but you've been dethroned.]. and if you're wondering, brenda's has the best shrimp and grits, but not the best beignets.

i'm currently a philosophy grad student. in college, i mostly
studied physics. the motivation has always been, you know, to
understand the nature of reality. career-wise, i'd love to stay in
academia forever. and i do literally mean "forever", or at least
"arbitrarily long" and certainly "past age 78"! i'm not sure how i
feel about eventually becoming a cyborg (the human-cyborg
transition would need to be sufficiently continuous to preserve my
personal identity), but i just don't see any way i'm going to to
complete my list of "things to think about at some point" that
doesn't involve extending my lifespan by at least a century or two.
also, i happen to like living!
essay2:
--constructing lengthy lingocular (linguistic-jocular) entities that require connecting perversely disparate ideas but which, when told, fail to have their intended effects realized as a result of overly complex grammatical form, overly self-referential semantic form, and/or insufficiently humorous content.

--devising profound-sounding statements that are completely devoid of any content, as in "one day, the light will come, and all will say, 'here, here!'  but not i; for when the light comes, i shall be free" and "the white tiger winks at the green bean."

--giving "glycosidic linkage" as a clue in the game "password".  (note: if you were born after 1950 and before 1970, feel free to replace "password" with "the $100,000 pyramid". if you were born between 1970 and 1994, feel free to replace "password" with "taboo". if you were born after 1994, you should probably... leave.)

in short, deviantly winning lingocularly.

really, though, pretty much any impression you get from this profile will be a reasonable indicator of the kind of impression you'd get from an actual conversation with me.  not a perfect indicator, of course. in reality, my personality traits are slightly less than those superficially indicated here: i'm slightly less self-referential, slightly less adept at uttering complete complex sentences, and so forth.  not very much less, but i did put some effort into crafting this profile, after all!  so what you see here is polished me.  polished me says "hello".

essay4:
books
well, i haven't really read much that's not related to my academic interests. but some fiction books/series i remember quite enjoying are the hitchhiker's guide to the galaxy, the neverending story, c.s. lewis' space trilogy, and 1984.  some "nonfiction" books i've enjoyed include goedel, escher, bach; david griffiths' physics books; and david lewis' on the plurality of worlds. i must also say that the crc handbook of chemistry and physics (86th ed.) is an absolutely thrilling read. i've probably read that little book nine times. personally, though, i think everything after the 87th edition is crap.

movies
some favorites: romantic comedies that feature meg ryan, romantic animated films that feature wall-e, sci-fi flicks that are not necessarily romantic but which feature y-wings, 2001, the sound of music, the truman show, being john malkovich, woody allen stuff. (note: i got into woody allen after people told me i reminded them of him, so please don't think i somehow idolize him! there are a lot of things about that man that shouldn't be... idolized.)

shows
among shows that are currently on the air, my 5 favorite are mad men, breaking bad, dexter, curb your enthusiasm, and peep show.  among shows that are now off the air, my 6 favorite are (possibly) lost, battlestar galactica, arrested development, the office (uk; and also the earlier days of the american version), seinfeld, and the larry sanders show.

music
limiting to 12 artists, and including them roughly in proportion with how often i listen to their respective genres: radiohead, sigur ros, arcade fire, muse, daft punk, beatles, beach boys, simon & garfunkel, tchaikovsky, beethoven, dvorak, wagner.

food
short answer: pizza. slightly longer answer: prior to a year ago, i disliked the taste of almost every food there is. (it's a long and, i'm told, fascinating story.) however, last summer i learned how to tolerate most (ordinary) foods, and i think i can say that i now even "like" many of them and actually enjoy the process of trying new things. that said, i'm still very ignorant about what foods are out there. so, show me some more food!

essay6:
the nature of (linguistic) meaning; the extent to which reality has any "structure"; the extent to which various metaphysical questions are substantive (e.g., are questions of existence to be settled merely by how we choose to use language?); the extent to which knowledge or justified belief is so much as possible (e.g., can i know that i'm not merely part of a computer simulation?); and a bunch of other issues in philosophy. i also spend a lot of time thinking about what issues i should be thinking about.

recently, my will caught up to my sense of rationality, and i'm now (very) often thinking about what i can do to be healthier. i seriously think that the changes i've made over the last several months have added a good 8 years to my life. only infinitely more to go!

i also often wonder about what would happen if i acted wildly inappropriately in a variety of social situations, like if i randomly started talking like yoda one day with my advisor or if i serenaded my mailman. would happen good results, hmm?

essay0:
i like to march to the beat of my own drum. i've traveled extensively around the world and believe the world is my oyster. i'm drawn to cultures different to my own and love the unbeaten track that takes me to new awakenings in life. yes i know the above sounds cliche, but i actually live it! i was born to hippy parents on a commune in tenn. where my parents had taken a vow of poverty. when i was two months old my family moved to guatemala to help in the relief efforts after an earthquake killed over 30,000 people and orphaned over 100,000 children. we lived there for 4 years after which we moved to california where we settled for about 6 years. we continued to travel about the country, actually 36 states (8 months), branching out to countries like thailand (6 months) and mexico (2 months) in search of the perfect haven. my parents never found their ideal place, but settled on gainesville, florida where i was home schooled along with my older sister till i graduated. i left home at 19 to live and work in a community for mentally handicapped people in upstate new york for a year. i then moved to paris, france as an au pair for another year. it was while in paris i discovered my love for salsa dancing. i had been dancing folkloric dance since i was 10 so always had a passion for dance, but not quite the passion i developed for salsa. i've been salsa dancing for over 14 years now and the sound of cuban salsa still makes my blood boil. after paris i returned to california where i continued as a nanny for a couple years. i had yet to find my calling in life so settled on caring for other people's children. i finally got certified to become a personal chef and have since then run my own personal chef and catering business (13 years). having traveled so much growing up i have always appreciated other cultures through traveling, food, music, and photography. my love for food is great, though my passion for photography is even greater. after 4 years of studying photography i'm now balancing my cooking and photography career.

these are just a few things that make me tick.

i love, food, travel, community, photography, laughter, the flavor of water when parched, the sound of children giggling uncontrollably, a child's hug, sleeping under the stars, the milky way, swimming naked at night, sleeping naked, chivalry, pranking, water fights, the smell of camp fires, the scent of wet earth, romance, sea glass hunting on the beach, artichokes, oysters, crab season, my cat's meow, the sun, being outside at all hours on hot humid nights, cuba, salsa dancing, old weathered hands that have a story, hearts of palm, nerds (candy), sushi, a first kiss, sex, my friends, spooning, world issues, sound of rain at night, playing in the rain, cooking for loved ones, hearing people's stories, road trips, big and little adventures, camping, making others laugh, laughing at myself, snuggles, etc..

if you share any love for the above mentioned then lets see if chemistry does the rest. .

btw, i won't respond to men over 45 years old.
also, sorry fellas, but i'm looking to meet someone who is 5'10" or taller.

i would describe myself as a good-humored and easy going woman who is youthful in my approach to life. i enjoy meeting people and doing things out and about. conversely, there are times when i just want to be quiet -- away from the crowd. ideally, quiet and at home (or on a road trip) with my partner, just enjoying spending time, touching (both physically and intellectually), laughing and sharing.

because i am tall, i project a certain confidence. i laugh from the heart and am fairly expressive. i am a natural hugger and tend to be open when interacting with people. yet there is a part of me that is shy, reserved and private.

i am optimistic and positive. i try to find the best out of every situation. i believe in god, prayer, miracles, and that good can come from challenging or negative situations. differences don't phase me, it's how you respond to those differences -- be they politics, race, or other. i am open to meeting and dating people from other cultures and races, as well as my own. in the end, it's about how we treat each other and the people we encounter everyday.

i work in public relations and am involved in a few community activities. service and compassion for others is important to me.

i enjoy music, good humor and like to travel. live contemporary jazz performances and latin jazz are among my favorites; gospel, classical, r&b complete the list but i appreciate all genres of music. stand up comedy makes me laugh. salsa dancing is my favorite past time. i am a native californian and enjoy exploring all that northern california offers. i also have traveled to different corners of the world.

my mind and my humor is wildly inappropriate. i mean no harm and

their inner light. i can be the heart of compassion and love when

and i like that about me. i adore learning about other cultures and
peoples and am always open to new information, the world changes
quickly and i firmly believe i need to change as rapidly as it

i'm a planner when it comes to big things. i like to know what's going on, and have a few backups as options. when it comes to the little things, i wing it more often than not.

ok, back to my regular profile...

i give up.

these are words that i've wanted to say countless times when it has come to the dating world. i'll admit, despite having been on a fair number of dates, it has not been an easy path and has oftentimes been frustrating. one can have so much faith into trying to make things work with someone until that someone completely rips your heart apart. yes, i've been there and like how most breakups go, it was not a smooth recovery. however, what can you do, but leave the past behind - life goes on and you really have no better choice to make than to pick yourself up and keep moving on. the world can indeed be a ruthless, cutthroat place sometimes, but the truth is, it's really in your hands whether you decide to sink or continue swimming.

i've honestly debated several times whether to delete my account and yet i'm still on here. why? because despite past mistakes and upsets i've experienced, i know that i can't give up. i can't allow others to get the best of me while constantly dwelling on my misfortunes. in addition, i've also had the opportunity to meet some great girls on here.

i might as well tell it straight up - i haven't had the privilege of many friends or much of a social life since college, but i do have a few good friends who stick by me. but even through such a shortcoming, i continue to enjoy life and seek out its many adventures. and hey, if you're the type of person who frowns or scoffs upon that, then please get off this profile - you've just proved to me you weren't worth dating in the first place.

if you've gotten this far in my profile, by the way, i appreciate the interest :) so moving on, what am i looking for in a girl? i need someone with a warm and sincere heart who will support and have faith in me. this might come as a surprise from what i've written here so far, but i do have a wacky sense of humor, so i need someone who i can share that with. i'm not on here for one-night stands or short-term relationships - i'm not even sure why anyone plans for a short-term relationship in the first place. it's like working towards a goal with the intention of already failing. to me, a relationship is a journey you share with someone filled with inevitable obstacles - what really matters in the end, is whether you're both capable of overcoming and learning from those obstacles together. i'm someone who treats every relationship as if it were my final one, but make no mistake - i'm not an idealist - i can't guarantee things will work out for good, but what i can guarantee, is that i tried my best while it lasted.

so if i messaged you, know that i did read your entire profile and that my message wasn't just something i spontaneously wrote while leaving the front door. anyways, thanks for making it this far in my profile and hopefully i can hear from you soon :)
essay1:
i graduated from usc with a masters degree in structural engineering and am currently working as a bridge engineer for a consulting firm. let's be real though - sure, it can be exciting at times seeing your bridge actually being constructed; sounding all professional and highly-esteemed to your typical gossipy asian parents; the pay is also great, but most of the time you're at a desk cranking out calculations, examining shop drawings, and running computer analyses endless times, that the work really does get dull sometimes.

if i didn't have to worry about financial burdens, what would my dream job ultimately be? a filmmaker and consider that my personal rebellion from the asian stereotype lol. i'm no lawyer, doctor, or accountant. that's right, i'm a part-time writer and director for my own film studio and i love doing it. maybe it's partly because i'm a left-hander, so i am creatively dominant :)

as for free time, i like to keep myself active while constantly expanding my knowledge. i try to hit the gym three times week and occasionally go for a run around my neighborhood. on my quieter days though, i'll grab a good book, watch a movie, work on my short films, or grab dinner with my best friend. you're not going to find me at clubs or bars getting drunk and passing out hehe - not my type of lifestyle.

when not sleeping in (which is not very often), i love to keep busy with friends and the outdoors. i enjoy exploring the city, finding new eateries, coffee shops, wine bars, street fairs, shopping, listening to and discovering new music, people watching in the park (not in a creepy way, people are just way too entertaining when they don't think anyone is looking!) and traveling. hopefully you can tell at this point that i like to be active!

i want someone with positive energy who enjoys drinks at a bar and also a bottle of wine at the house. i want someone to meet me half-way and feel like they are also "the lucky one" in the relationship. i want it all!!

i work as a chef. food is definitely a passion, and my means of giving back to others and the people around me. and if we get along, and i actually like you, i may even cook for you one day.

if i could characterize myself with just a couple words, it would be "artsy intellectual". i get bored with routine, am constantly seeking new challenges, perspectives, tips, and techniques. i do not view change as instability, i view it as necessary for evolving as a person. paradoxically, i also simultaneously seek to maintain stability in my life. i've had someone ask me if i was a poet. someone else said that i really reminded her of clark kent. this does not in any way mean that i claim to be superman. i mean, would you honestly wear tights like that, if you were compensated with superpowers? i think it is a tossup.

oh, and there is also quite a lot of writer in me.
essay1:
recently returned from a little foray into european cookery - cooked at a luxury hotel in dublin, and one of the top restaurants in london. while in london, i spent entire days (16 hr workdays) holed up in a submarine-like kitchen in the soho district, which required me to open a hatch on the sidewalk and climb down a ladder to access. i suppose they removed the periscope at some point, although it certainly would have come in handy. and working side by side with some surly, albeit very talented brits. a great experience, but as the british might say, "can't be bothered" to do 80 hour weeks ever again.

i'm now cooking at a restaurant which, if you keep up with the michelin guide, you probably know about.

i developed quite a passion for travel photography whilst in europe, and have dabbled with food photography and portraiture. if i find you worthy, i might even give you a gift of a photoshoot. i've only ever done that once for someone. too time consuming, with all the editing involved.

i have also recently picked up golf. quite the hacker at this time, but one of the beautiful things about golf is that it truly is a lifetime sport.

essay1:
i spent a lot of years getting paid to sit in front of a computer. a couple of huge faceless corporations and a bunch of startups (my own, others'). some successful and some, well, not. i've mostly tried to get away from that and so now i run a commercial cabinet and furniture woodshop over there on the edge of town.

i spend a ton of my free time sitting on a bicycle. when the noise and dust pile up, there's almost nothing better than to ride off to some faraway mountain and look at things from on top. or a distant beach and jump in the ocean.

and to earn actual money, i'm the c-something-o of a small (but spunky!) energy services company. we explain to municipal governments how to build renewable local power generation, where to put it, and how to pay for it.

books: i like a book that takes forever to get through. i've been reading the brothers karamazov for seventeen years. engineering textbooks. pynchon, gaddis, nabokov, perec. i've recently plowed through a bunch of willa cather and louisa may alcott. i got a kindle for christmas and, initially skeptical but, i've just been zipping through books lately: most of flannery o'conner, the book thief, the master and margarita are probably the highlights .. even some new stuff.

movies: i haven't had a television since i left my parents' house a million years ago and i don't see many movies. but: anything by tarkovsky or miyazaki. alphaville. and cloudy with a chance of meatballs in imax 3d was a riot.

humor! i was told to inject humor into my profile by my friends. let's see, the past, the present and the future walk into a bar. it was tense..

ah, it's almost summer. so many things to do! festivals, music in the square, concerts...

what might life with me be like? two weekends ago, a group of my friends and i filled up some picnic baskets full of goodies and headed out to a local winery. after purchasing a few bottles, we laid out a spread in the patio area and relaxed and enjoyed the sunshine.

last weekend i went wandering around the city, acting like a tourist and reconnecting with some places i hadn't been to in awhile.

there are some trails around me that i like to hike, especially if the weather is good. i'm a decent skier although i don't get into the mountains as often as i would like.

i like to keep busy. i'm not much of a tv watcher, just the occasional show now and then. i prefer to spend time writing, practicing my piano, and this may come as a surprise but i am a quilter. yes, a quilter. it's something i picked up many years ago and just kept on doing.

i love conversation, and would love to have someone to talk to for hours, over coffee, wine or whatever. i've been in radio for over 27 years and i feel i've lived a fairly fascinating life, and have plenty of stories to keep you entertained.

i'm a positive, upbeat, "glass half full" kind of guy. i could be your biggest cheerleader.

so what have i left out? how about elephant races down the streets of long beach? (i came in last, earning the coveted "golden shovel" award) i estimate i've seen at least 500 concerts. i've lived in many different parts of the country, including albuquerque, houston, tampa and rochester ny. i've crossed the country 5 times, and wouldn't mind doing it for a 6th.

so, have i said enough? would you like to know more?

i'm moses.

i learned this two decades ago at the marin psychic fair. or faire. i forget which. psychic reader magazine had a coupon for free admission. i also forget why anyone i know had a copy of psychic reader magazine.

but we went. and on the way there i was saying how in past lives nobody ever seems to have been some unknown peasant. they were always famous royalty or some other historical bigshot like moses. i have two friends who will swear i said it.

and we went in. we had palm readings and aura readings and tarot readings and some other reading involving hopefully non-toxic crystals before we got to the past lives booth. i went first. the psychic said she was getting a very clear picture of the ancient me: swirling sand ... pyramids ... a baby floating on a river. "moses! you were moses!" she was so happy for me. others waiting in line were very impressed.

if you need a large body of water parted for a few hours, let me know.

i get lost all the time. i can ride the subway in the wrong direction and not notice. i can drive past an exit on the highway and not realize until miles later. once, i walked right into a stranger's apartment without thinking.

actually, the problem is that i think too much. basketball, politics, music, even management theory i get lost in thought over all kinds of subjects.

i also get lost in cycling. i've been doing it two times a week for about eight years. i like to cycle up san bruno mountain and back; sometimes i'll go across the golden gate bridge across to marin. it's an activity where i get to test myself and try to obtain a new goal each time.

i like a challenge. i joined toastmasters to get over my fear of public speaking and now i love it so much that i even compete. it also helps with presentations i do for work (i'm with the feds). that said, i'm a quiet guy and a good listener. besides my own thoughts, i like to know what's going on in someone else's mind.

masculine, laid-back tech guy here. looking around, hoping to make friends, eventually meet that special someone. i'm not in a big rush. mainly because i've fallen flat on my face a few times when i was rushing.

i know i'll be mr. right for someone and vice-versa. in the meantime, i'm going to enjoy the ride and hopefully frolic with the squirrels and not frighten them too badly. they have nuts to protect after all. um, read into that what you will.

i'm the scruffed-out guy-next-door-type and attracted to similar on through the bear-ish side of the community. never been attracted to the fem guys.

warm, sociable. kind-hearted. it shines best in small groups. in large, public places i tend to be a lot more quiet if i'm by myself or don't know anyone.

i'm a bit of a geek. i love gaming when i have the time for it. i collected comic books as a kid. i design and code software for a living. unlike a lot of geeks though, i'm very much about health and fitness, the counter balance to sitting at a desk in front of a monitor all day!

it would be easy for others to see me as a loner, but at heart i'm really not. like a lot of us, i just happen to be a mid-life guy in a job the gives me security with too little vacation time and i'm usually worn out by the end of the day. i'm taking tips on how to change that!

random other bits about me:

* have master's degrees in both computer science and theater
* interests: reading, cutting edge tech (including nano-, bio- and a.i.), food, travel, movies, outdoor recreation of various kinds, exploring national parks and the like, astronomy, museums, theater, and lots of other stuff
* grew up in alaska ... so i know how to treat hypothermia if you need someone to warm you back up
* love all kinds of animals; owner of a really cool cat
* been out since 1984! family is supportive.
* i've never had a psycho boyfriend who left me broken, jaded, and mistrustful of relationships.
* i have only ever been clean-shaven face for a handful of brief periods in my adult life.
* i look awful with a military/shaved haircut. i just don't have the right shape of head for it.
* i am clueless when it comes to divas that a lot of gay guys love to follow.

feel free to ask to find out more.

:)

essay0:
i'm a fun-loving, hard-working foodie and lawyer. i'm laid back, have a good sense of humor and love to learn new things. i moved to san francisco a couple of years ago, and while i love the warmth and lifestyle out here, i'll always be a new yorker at heart. that said, i'm excited to be living here and have no plans to move.

i love to travel, explore, hike, run, ski, play volleyball, etc. and try to do so as much as possible. i also like catching up on sleep, movies and tv. while i've spent a fair amount of time traveling abroad, i'm excited to take advantage of all the local options. right now, renting a house in big sur or wine country for a short vacation, spending the days hiking/running, reading and cooking sounds perfect.

i'm looking for a guy who challenges me and likes being challenged. i can be sarcastic and witty. i can dish it and take it. i'm looking for someone who is tall, masculine, affectionate, proactive, and interested in getting to know me. i'm pretty social and outgoing, so you'd likely be someone who is frequently up for going out, can drive a conversation, and can get along with a variety of people. that said, i love lazy sundays and cooking at home. i've done a few stints as a pastry chef in various restaurants both here and in nyc, so a sweet tooth is a must :)

friends and family are paramount for me, so i spend a lot of time catching up with them over the phone, over drinks, while hiking or checking out a museum or comedy club. hopefully you're someone who is comfortable hanging out with friends and meeting new people, as well as grabbing dinner and a movie.

i know there are probably a lot of people on okc looking for casual or short-term relationships, which i totally respect. i'm not looking to force anything serious, but i am at a point in my life where i'm excited for a great long-term relationship.

i am snuggly, gregarious, and optimistic.

fiction: i recently read two excellent debut novels: the quantum thief by hannu rajaniemi, and liminal states by zack parsons. i'm about halfway through wildwood by colin meloy. i've read all of the song of ice and fire (a.k.a. game of thrones) books, think that the hunger games trilogy goes downhill after the first book, and read an embarrassing number of laurell k. hamilton books before i realized that they had turned entirely into bodice-ripping fanservice.

non-fiction: lately i've found myself reading a lot of books about the cultural impact of technology, mostly video games (tom bissell, jane mcgonigal, harold goldberg, steven johnson, the new collection of william gibson articles). i'm also technically re-reading susan sontag's on photography, but let's just say that progress is slow.

music: i mostly listen to music like: stars, the new pornographers, the decemberists, yeah yeah yeahs, though lately i've been going through a mainstream pop/dance music phase, due to my new daily commute down to the peninsula (it keeps me awake while i drive). sleater-kinney is my favorite band of all time. i have a fondness for hip-hop as seen through the lens of mash-up djs like girl talk and the white panda.

photography: i love the 60's moma school of photography (robert frank, lee friedlander, garry winogrand, william eggleston, etc). the americans is one of my favorites. i also like eugne atget. as for contemporary photographers, nikki s. lee does some really interesting work.

tv: i try to keep up with: 30 rock, archer, being human, bones, castle, downton abbey, house, parks and recreation, portlandia. past favorites include: bsg, firefly, veronica mars.

food: one of the reasons i love living in this city is the availability of high-quality food, high-class to hole-in-the-wall. i only wish i had more opportunities to discover new eats.

games: recent favorites include: bioshock, spacechem, civilization 5, skyrim, arkham city, and the mass effect and dead space series. i like all the 2d zelda games, except for zelda ii. i don't understand a lot of the stuff coming out of japan these days.

essay0:
"i don't normally do this, but i felt compelled to tell you something. you have an absolutely breath-taking hieney. i mean, that thing's good. i wanna be friends with it."- ron burgundy, 2004.

yes, i enjoy quoting stupid movies. yes, i think it's a completely appropriate first impression. disagree? no worries, stick me with a poor rating and move onto the next candidate who'd rather give you his resume, list his accomplishments, and hope you see that picture of him in his shiny ride. personally, i'd say this is the time for candor about who i am and what i'm looking for... so there you are, me in a nutshell. if we can't laugh together, we could never be in eachother's lives, at least not intimately. you would tire of my never ending shenanigans - my goofatude would wear on your frail nerves, and frankly, i would get bored and begin chewing on the legs of the antique coffee table your grandmother gave you; digging; barking incessantly. let's not allow that to happen.

phew okay, with that off my chest, let me say that i can absolutely be serious, not to worry. i am a professional. period. i work from home, have the discipline to be successful in such an environment, and love the time that it gives me to focus on the things that make me smile. what are those things? anything outdoors and physical. i am a crossfit fanatic - i gave up on the globo-gyms of the world long ago. keep it fresh, and intensely difficult, and i'm a happy man. recent back surgery brought me back down to earth for a bit, but i'm back baby! yes, i did just use the word "back" three times in the same sentence. but that's what life is about, i've learned - take the good with the bad and move on... and use healthy number of cliches when describing your self to strangers.

i am a die hard giants fan; 2010 was magical - and not just because krup and kuip said so. the niners hold a special place in my heart as well... sadly that place is currently filled with the tears of kittens, and tinkerbell's nightmares. it's tough to be a niner fan, and it doesn't look like this year will be much better. i will cry at some point this season. what!? you said you wanted a man who was willing to express himself! can't have it both ways. [update: i wrote this before the season started... i won't say more b/c i don't want to jinx them - go niners! ** new update: yes, i cried. i now officially hate the nyg. but i'm grateful for the nfc championship, and am trying my best to remain positive for next year's prospects].
my idea of the perfect sunday is waking up early, running around the lagunitas and bon tempe lakes in marin, coming home, and resting my derriere comfortably in front of the tube to soak up a full day of football. and yes ladies, if that doesn't do it for you, i am also a card-carrying fantasy football nerd to boot - hot, right!?

family. it's small - i mean my family, get your mind of out the gutter, please - but they mean the world to me. i was raised by my mother and two grandmothers, and cherish the influence these women have had on my life. i am forever grateful!

as for what i'm looking for, i'm hoping its obvious. someone who is active and fun; someone to share the outdoors with; someone who agrees that laughter is the key to a solid relationship; it must be present, it must be hearty, it must not sound like a donkey. i have a puppy, so being a dog-person is non-negotiable. if you don't like puppies, there is something fundamentally wrong with you. i mean that in the most endearing way i assure you, but please, don't bother. other than that, surprise me. i'm up for just about anything!

la native, bay area settled. former techie (cs) who really wanted to cook turned into art degree woodworker who bartends and hates cooking for myself. i still love to cook, just for others and with others. if i really like you, i'll cook for you. i guess you could say i'm multi faceted, and it would be hard to find another soul who shares the same interests. but isn't that the point of dating? the search for others who you find attractive but who can mentally stimulate you through conversation and physical activities can be annoying and frustrating, but the realization of who you are and what you actually want is what i've learned through this roller coaster of life. however, i fear i've gone a little too philosophical on your beautiful eyeballs (i'll just assume you have beautiful eyes, haha!)

let's talk about food. this is a must passion, hobby, interest, and necessity. some women have fashion and shoes (two totally separate entities i've learned), i have food. i live pretty simply but splurge on ephemeral experiences that invovle taste bud popping, laugh inducing fun, and moments where you go "omg wtf was that?". it doesn't have to be a 32 course meal at el bulli (but would be mind blowing). it could be a simple fresh salad with amazing ingredients and dressing; just something that triggers memories of a good time and mouth tingling food.

me, as a person, well..... i am a big man in a compact frame who is overly generous and considerate to almost being a fault. i have a lot of interests but only focus on a few, but always want to try new things. not really a picture guy. i should update my pics, but i really don't have that many. i have a 5 second rule for dining pictures. you have 5 seconds to take a picture of my food before i start digging in, and definitely no flash.

i grew up in a small town in northern california under the auspices
of a special ed teacher and an entrepreneur. i rode horses, stalked
banana slugs, and generally had an uproarious time before heading
to brown. well, that's not exactly true, but i can attest to the
luck associated with kissing the aforementioned yellow gastropod. i
started school studying neuroscience before switching to the dark
(arts) side. i moved to nyc in 2006 where i shacked up with a
paramedic in an east village tenement with no shower and the
bathtub in the kitchen. i fondly remember returning home nights to
find un-insured friends being stitched up in said bathtub. it's
been years since i've inquired, why is our bathroom covered in
blood? while in new york, i got a masters from nyu and spent a
year doing a writing fellowship. three years ago i moved to
southern california to take up surfing, teach writing, and get an
mfa. highlights include narrowly escaping getting voted off
graduate student council for losing a bunch of money on a drag
ballet, annual grunion runs, and writing a new musical with an
arkansas based casio-pop band. i'm excited to be back in the bay
area. my first order of business may or may not be (but definitely
is) getting drunk and going to the exploratorium.

well for starters i don't capitalize on the internet. pointlessly holding shift every couple of words is weird and illogical. there are periods for a reason. if you asked me i honestly couldn't tell you a good reason to capitalize the beginning of every sentence.

as a result of falling in the autistic spectrum i'm a bit ocd about tactile stimuli. one time someone was referring to how you don't feel your clothes all the time while you're wearing them and i was like "what are you talking about 0.o" this makes me weird in a couple ways. if you're curious then go ahead and ask.

if you've seen the first episode of how i met your mother then you can understand when i say that i identify a crap ton with what ted says to robbin at the end of that episode about being terrible at being single and all that.

another good thing to add. (i'm just putting these in here as they come to mind) i will, for whatever reason, eventually have not much to say over the internet. i am an in person personality. i can't remember who said it but it's been said that all relationships are based on shared experiences and texting over the internet doesn't seem like much of an experience. so, if you think maybe you might like to meet eventually then that's bonus points in my book.

(edit. ( i'm running out of steam when it comes to online interaction. i know it's almost a taboo in our culture to meet someone from the internet after learning very little about them but it's so much faster and more effective to just meetup. assuming i were an evil person out to do bad things. i don't have magic powers that make you come with me to a dangerous place or anything like that. if we meet in person at a coffee shop there is very little risk being run there. i say this because i am terrible online. i'm bad at whatever it is you need to do to keep someone interested. in person i'm much better. i'm a great deal more experienced in face to face communication. body language is great and tone+timing are what i rely on to actually be funny at all. that being the key ingredient to the majority of human relations it can be hard for me to make much of a connection through text. so all that being said. if you'd like to meet in person please just tell me. i wont get weird about it or be scared off. however if you want to talk first that's fine too. just, i'm bad at reading between the lines when there are actually lines of text to be read between so if you're genuinely interested don't be afraid to be blunt about it. in fact i'd prefer it.)

update / warning: i currently have a beard not depicted in the posted photographs. it all started when i installed linux on my laptop, and i believe the beard and operating system have developed some kind of codependency which i can't quite figure out yet. i apologize in advance. thank you for your understanding in this matter, we now return to our introduction, already in progress:

i am a cartoon character, apparently. i'm also a neuvo-retro-ex-post-nihilist , or whatever the kids are calling it now. (which isn't to be confused with an ambivalist or anarchist, though i've been known to keep company with some). while i'd hope it would go without saying, i don't use the term "bisexual" to imply that i'm only attracted to two chromosome-determined genders, i'm down for all combinations of queerness and faggotry. i'm an east bay native, but not for lack of trying. i don't get out enough to know whether or not i'm a stereotype or a hipster, and i don't get why people my age spend so much time trying to undermine one another's authenticity. i'm big on autonomy, very opposed to identity politics. i probably have that attention deficit thing the news is always on about. i generally follow the savage love school of thought on romantic matters and the roger ebert side of cinema. also, i'm pretty sure i'm a pomosexual. my body, though occasionally metaphorical, is not a temple. i only own two pairs of shoes at a given time, but compulsively hoard most other things.

i don't know how to talk about myself without sounding like a wanker; though i have surprising eloquence for someone with such little sophistication.

essay1:
in the past 5 years i've lived in austin, seattle, new york and san francisco. my dad says this makes me like a tumbleweed (no roots), but that comes from a man who refused to visit me in new york because his being mugged in chicago thirty years before. i try to live in whichever city can teach me the most.

i love ideas, big & small, old & new. i get excited about absurd little things, like a more elegant way to tie my shoes (the ian knot), and big distant things, like new ways to organize society, or the possibility of making the oceans the next frontier.

i love art, in any medium. the kind that touches a nerve, that inspires you, or makes you clench your teeth, or makes you cry from the depth of your humanity.

i do web consulting for pay, and work on my own projects otherwise. working for myself is both liberating and demanding... i can live where i want, travel when i want - but i also have to be the one looking over my own shoulder to get things done.

i do what i can to end up in unusual places - a surreal art opening, a giant leather street fair, a music festival populated by artists who'd invented their own instruments, a party held illegally in the catacombs of paris, or a talk on neurophysiology and quantum mechanics.

i've been on a fitness kick recently, so chances are before long i'd want to drag you out to the gym, yoga, biking, skiing, or rock climbing.

my humor is absurd, extra-dry and generally served with a smirk and a wink.

i am a northern california native. raised by artists. i value honesty and direct communication. i have taken a long look inside and done more then my share of personal work. that said... i am human. a work in progress. i have learned to love myself and others through excepting our perfect imperfections. we are all so beautifully flawed. i live creatively. the people that know me a bit would say i am smart, funny, outgoing, and confident. the ones that know me better would say i am fragile, sensitive, devoted, and old fashioned.

the most important thing in life to me is connecting in a meaningful way with other people.

the second most important thing in life to me is living with beautiful surroundings. this can mean my home, fresh flowers, travel to distant countries, mountains, trees, city views, tasty food from the garden, interior design, art, fashion, all types of dance, music, people,.... you? i am a romantic at heart. sensitive to all things beautiful.

i am not looking to get into a relationship just for the sake of being with someone. i would be thrilled to fall in love! i welcome it with open arms. not with any great guy but with the right great guy for me. we all deserve that! for now i am having a lovely time getting to know people. being single is pretty great but i believe committed relationships are the braver and more rewarding road to take. when it's the right choice....

as for the kind of man i would love to meet? we will recognize each other when we meet. we will just.. connect. make each other laugh. trust each other easily. you will dance with me if not in public then when we are alone. maybe you will teach me how to push myself athletically in nature... whether that means surfing, hiking and camping, the snow, the wild... i don't care. i will trust you enough to take me on an adventure. or maybe you will push my intellect, or my creativity. i will certainly enhance yours..
you are strong and balanced. you will have a way of keeping things simple. passionate and proud of what you do. i can inspire you! you will inspire the devoted and passionate parts of me as well... you are a very responsible and committed man. you are deep, sexy, fun, and alive. you know yourself and are not afraid to go after your dreams.

all other qualities i will be surprised and delighted by when we meet. looking forward to meeting you.

i was really halfway anxious about meeting cool people on this site
until i realized i had to write several college level essays to
fill out my profile. can't do it!

i have been thinking that i should update this for a while... but never knowing what to write. what should i add? what should i take away?

who am i today? how have my experiences reshaped the person that i would to be, when i awoke this morning? how have the choices, both good and bad, from my past, affected my personality, and who i am to be tomorrow?

i have re read the last self summary, and while some of it did sound like me, still some other parts don't clearly represent who i have become since that point.

so who am i today?

i am someone who constantly battles the part of myself, that i don't like, and would not want to pass those character traits to another person.

i'm finding that i don't really much like dating. friendships are okay, but i feel better if i am moving forward toward something, more in the relationship department. and because of this, i tend to come on more strongly than i mean to. if friendships are the only thing that someone is interested in with me, i would like to know bluntly, so that i know better not to get my heart attached.

while chatting with someone here, i was told that i should add my part of the conversation to my profile page.... so here it is:

"i know that i am looking for someone too, but that "woman" always changes from my point of view, and what goes on in my life
like, for the changing perspectives... of what i am looking for...
it would be great to have a friend, someone that i can talk to.
it would be great to have a buddy that i can go to the bars with, and to the coffee shops.
and it would be great that i could find someone that i could be intimate with as well
but i'm not finding one person for all of those things."

i am someone who likes children, and i enjoy the way that they look at life. sometimes reminding me of points of view, that i have forgotten.

i'm someone that needs a woman that has a backbone; some one who can challenge me.

i am someone who seems to influence others lives, without trying.

as life goes by, thoughts change, opinions change, and growth happens. i say that to say this... in the past, i have answered 1300 or so questions, and sometimes answers and reasons change. and i don't take the time to go through all of my answers, to alter how i think... so don't just take for granted that what i answered, when i answered it... is the same way that i believe it now. if you have a questions, or something doesn't seem to line up with what your "match" is... you can either ask me about it, for clarification.... or you can assume, and then be wrong in your assumption. (6/20/2012)

i've always been a bit hesitant to join one of these online dating sites, it just doesn't seem normal to me to meet someone on here but i guess it's worth a shot...it is the future and the fate of mankind or so i'm told. i guess i'm kind of bitter towards these types of sites because i'm a bit of a romantic. i would much rather meet you through a chance encounter, and endure the thrill of the chase, if you will.

my ideal scenario is seeing you from across the bar for the first time as i make my way through the crowd, we catch glimpses of each other throughout the evening and i ultimately gain the courage to buy you a drink or strike up a random conversation when you ask me for a light because you only smoke cigarettes when you drink, like me. i would get your number and hope that you'll pick up the phone when i call and you actually agree to meet me somewhere for a second encounter all our own.

oh, wait this section is supposed to be about me and not how i wish to meet you.

anyways, i just recently moved to the bay area for a job opportunity. i'm a texas native, born and raised. i've lived in three cities in the past three years, because of the industry i work in but i put up with it because it's always been my dream to be a part of it. plus, i can't really complain about moving to the bay area, it's quite lovely. texas was two extremes, either really hot or really cold and you never get used to it.

getting off topic again.......where was i? oh yes, telling you about me!

well, on the weekends i like going to dive bars, listening/watching live music, hanging out with friends in the city and just generally being out and about, i'm pretty easy going.

is this enough info, is there a character limit to this section...i wonder how long it will go for, if i just keep on ranting? ah, it's not worth your time, i'll just stop right here.

i don't know what the other ladies on this site are writing, so i have no idea if what i'm about to say is original or not, but i can promise you it's 100% authentic and honest.

i'm a california girl with an appreciation for the small things in life. i am settling back into life in the us after spending a year in germany. i grew up in southern california but i've dreamed of moving to sf since i was about 4 years old and watched the intro to full house over and over again...

i believe life is all about balance and moderation. i once took a test to see if i was more type a or b, and the test concluded that i was exactly half and half, haha. i enjoy the mountains as much as the ocean and camping as much as fine dining. i'm not into going out every night - i like the idea of going out some nights and then having a few quiet nights at home. i am a glass half-full, silver lining type person. my belief is that we have the power to create our thoughts, good or bad, and so i like to spend my energy on the good!

family and friends are very important to me, so i spend a lot of my time with them. i tend to keep a few really close friends rather than tons of mediocre friends, and i wouldn't have it any other way! i am a very even-keeled person who tends to remain calm through a storm, so i adopt to role of "steady rock" in many people's lives.

things i love: dancing, music, cheesy jokes, chocolate chip cookies, spontaneous adventures, and making lists =)

so i hope that let you get to know a little about me (we should save some mystery)...i am looking for someone who enjoys traveling, conversation, being active, and enjoying the simple things in life. i want to be with someone who pushes me to be, learn, and experience more, and somebody who appreciates me for who i am: good, bad, and dorky.

if you got this far, take a chance and let's see if we hit it off! =)

some of my favorite books of all time are catch-22 and the hitchhiker's guide to the galaxy. good books that i've read since moving out to california include the dispossessed, pillars of the earth, shalimar the clown, and darwin's dangerous idea. authors i've read a lot of recently include neal stephenson, john le carre, iain banks, and richard morgan. reputable books that i've subjected myself to recently in the name of broadening my literary horizons include ulysses, atlas shrugged, and the brothers karamazov.

my musical fare is mostly progressive rock and progressive metal. some of my favorite bands include porcupine tree, dream theater, opeth, riverside (the polish one), green carnation, pure reason revolution, chroma key, blackfield, arcturus, and pineapple thief. classical composers i enjoy include prokofiev and grieg. a few more mainstream artists i like are pink floyd, leonard cohen, and nine inch nails.

i like flavorful and spicy food. i enjoy cooking my own chili, with generous quantities of serrano and habanero peppers. i love indian curries and thai or chinese stir fries. i'm not a huge seafood eater, but i can eat a few kinds of sushi. i detest mushrooms.

essay1:
i am enjoying life in san francisco. i moved here in july of 2010
after living in la. i grew up in florida, so i am a little wimpy about the cold! i am toughing it out, though, because i think sf is such a
wonderful place. all the amazing things this city has to offer make up for the weather. i like that the people here are smart, adventurous, open minded, and friendly.

i am in medical device sales and work for a company that makes
spinal implants. i was a sales rep for a long time and have now
moved into a specialist position. i travel around the western
united states recruiting, training, and supporting sales reps who
sell products to spine and orthopedic surgeons. yes, i do go into
the or! you get used to it.

on weekends, i enjoy spending time with the wonderful friends i
have met in sf. i love running and have recently tried to pick up
road biking. i enjoy hiking, but also enjoy a leisurely walk around
the city. i love being out and about and trying new restaurants, but i also enjoy cooking dinner at home. i am usually up for any type of sf exploring--gg park, museum, shops or flea market, theater or live music, etc.

i have traveled quite a bit--all over europe (lived in spain for a
semester in college), israel, jordan, morocco, brazil, costa rica,
several islands in the caribbean, tahiti, thailand, japan, and
china. i prefer trips that are not structured on a tour bus.
sometimes instead of a big trip, i just go home to go to the beach
with my family and have just as much fun.

my family is very important to me. they are 4 of the people i look
up to most in the world. i have 2 little sisters, and my parents
are still together. i have 2 precious twin 4 year old nephews whom
i couldn't love more. i visit them about 4 times a year in fl. i am
thankful to have grown up surrounded by loving, caring, inspiring
people. my grandparents are no longer alive, but i think
of them often. they believed in giving--giving back to the
community financially and with your time, giving to our family, and
they also frequently reminded us to live in the moment and enjoy
life.

i love kids and definitely want to have a family one day when i
meet the right person. even though my family is far from here, i picture myself staying in the sf area.

part of what i love about sf is the historical buildings. i live in
a building that was built in 1901. i love the quirkiness, the
character, the architecture, the molding, etc. of old homes. i
enjoy working on the house and always seem to be working on some type of project.

i do not have any pets at the moment but would love to get a dog
one day. i grew up with dogs and love them.

hi and thanks for checking out my profile :-) i prefer to wander trails rather than follow freeways; i am both conventional and a nonconformist. i know my history, my faults, and am (always trying to) consciously live in the present. i am not perfect but with a good sense of humor and patience (you and) i can laugh and learn along the way. i'm spunky, vivacious, happy, spontaneous and sensual. i am comfortable in my own skin. while i am grounded, i sometimes have one foot off the ground for good reason! :) on that note, please don't be too judgmental on what falls in/out bounds. my friends say that i'm smart, articulate, generous and have good intentions, and that i live very well.

i have 2 teenagers who are my top priority, but i know how to make time for myself.

creativity, inspiration, kindness, lightness, confidence (not ego) and intelligence are what attract me. i admire men who are self-made, have purpose and dreams! there is no perfect formula or list here... i can see you as an individual and don't judge. i tend to communicate with words, touch, and if we're lucky, on a higher level. it's important that i am with someone who is spiritual and aware of how interconnected we all are. this, of course, requires empathy and sensitivity.

online, here on okc, i hope to find friends. it begins with dating, and eventually we figure out if our minds, souls, and lives can wander within the same course. it's not too complicated; i like to keep it as simple as possible.

i'm interested in only one truly honest relationship... building just one spiritual, deeply intimate, connection. anything else is fine, as friends.

i am truthful, to a fault, and don't see any reason for pretenses, deception, or games. if that's what you bring, then please save us both the time.

if you're the man i seek, then let's stop wasting time and jump on that journey -- there are incredible things, ideas, and adventures to explore. let's live life with laughter, light, and love! i'm ready and willing to open my heart to the right man.

on average, i get 6 visitors to my okc profile per week and 1 message. a female friend of mine gets 20 messages per day, with a superficial profile and a single picture. she is somewhat hotter than i am, to be fair.

there are a few thing that i've learned in my short life:

1. there's no worse feeling than that millisecond you're sure you are going to die after leaning your chair back a little too far.
2. nothing sucks more than that moment during an argument when you realize you're wrong.
3. bad decisions make good stories.

on that note, my father once told me that, at the end of my life, i would remember the experiences i had not the items i purchased. i take this to heart each and every day and consciously put myself into situations where i will have the opportunity to meet new people, learn new things or at least have an interesting story to tell a friend.

people always describe me as a "nice guy" and i don't see this as a bad thing. i'm an excellent friend, the first person people call when they need a favor and always go the extra mile to help someone out.

food - i'm currently in the market for cooking classes. i enjoy food and pretty much eat anything but am really interested in learning more about how to cook. i really envy the people that can look in their cupboard and refrigerator and think up a meal. right now, if i don't have a recipe, i am pretty much out of luck.
